00:02:33.685 --> 00:02:34.625
VINT CERF: Fair deal.

00:02:34.625 --> 00:02:36.500
WALTER ISAACSON: The
main thing I discovered.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:39.620
I've written biographies
a lot-- Steve Jobs,

00:02:39.620 --> 00:02:42.150
Einstein, Franklin--
and those of us

00:02:42.150 --> 00:02:46.050
who write biographies kind of
know in the back of our minds

00:02:46.050 --> 00:02:49.850
that we distort history with
the great man theory of history.

00:02:49.850 --> 00:02:52.820
We make it sound like there's
a guy or a gal in a garage

00:02:52.820 --> 00:02:56.750
or a garret who has a light bulb
moment and innovation happens.

00:02:56.750 --> 00:03:00.320
True innovation, and there's
no better example of it

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:05.680
then the ARPANET RFC process
and then the TCP/IP process,

00:03:05.680 --> 00:03:08.290
really comes from pairs of
people, teams of people,

00:03:08.290 --> 00:03:13.270
and from collaboration, bouncing
ideas off against each other,

00:03:13.270 --> 00:03:16.060
finishing each
other's sentences,

00:03:16.060 --> 00:03:18.910
and the internet
age in particular

00:03:18.910 --> 00:03:21.610
allows such teamwork
and collaboration.

00:03:21.610 --> 00:03:24.950
The other thing was I started
this book when I said,

00:03:24.950 --> 00:03:27.250
way earlier before
we started, we

00:03:27.250 --> 00:03:30.810
were talking about when I ran
digital media for Time Inc

00:03:30.810 --> 00:03:35.410
in the early 1990s, and I first
met Vint when he was at MCI,

00:03:35.410 --> 00:03:38.550
and I was trying to convince
Time Inc to do things

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:39.880
with the internet.

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:42.680
And so the president of
Time Inc says to me, well,

00:03:42.680 --> 00:03:44.820
who owns the internet?

00:03:44.820 --> 00:03:46.774
So first of all,
I think to myself

00:03:46.774 --> 00:03:48.190
because I don't
want to get fired,

00:03:48.190 --> 00:03:49.520
that's a clueless question.

00:03:49.520 --> 00:03:50.750
I say, nobody owns it.

00:03:50.750 --> 00:03:52.810
He says, well, who built it?

00:03:52.810 --> 00:03:54.380
Who created it?

00:03:54.380 --> 00:03:56.680
And I realized
after thinking how

00:03:56.680 --> 00:04:00.130
clueless that question was
that I did not really now.

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:03.680
And if you feel detached from
the history of the things you

00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:09.440
use, there's sort of a
detachment that leads to you

00:04:09.440 --> 00:04:11.650
not feeling comfortable with it.

00:04:11.650 --> 00:04:15.390
So I wanted to know, how
did computers happen?

00:04:15.390 --> 00:04:18.380
How did the PC happen?

00:04:18.380 --> 00:04:20.279
How did the transistor
become the microchip,

00:04:20.279 --> 00:04:25.410
and then how did the internet or
digital packet switch networks

00:04:25.410 --> 00:04:27.270
come into being?

00:04:27.270 --> 00:04:31.380
So that's why I did this book,
and in doing so, as I said,

00:04:31.380 --> 00:04:33.380
you learn about the
importance of collaboration,

00:04:33.380 --> 00:04:34.880
but you also learn
that there wasn't

00:04:34.880 --> 00:04:37.520
one person who
invented the computer.

00:04:37.520 --> 00:04:39.329
And certainly, even
after doing this book,

00:04:39.329 --> 00:04:41.120
you and I have been
discussing some of the,

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:44.270
no, I should get more
credit type feelings,

00:04:44.270 --> 00:04:48.570
but it was done creatively
and collaboratively.

00:04:48.570 --> 00:04:50.660
VINT CERF: This notion
of collaboration

00:04:50.660 --> 00:04:52.960
resonates very
well with all of us

00:04:52.960 --> 00:04:56.880
at Google because a lot of
the tools that we make and use

00:04:56.880 --> 00:04:59.130
are exactly
collaborative elements,

00:04:59.130 --> 00:05:01.790
things like Shared Documents,
things like the Google

00:05:01.790 --> 00:05:04.040
Hangouts, things like that
where multiple parties can

00:05:04.040 --> 00:05:06.670
communicate all
at the same time.

00:05:06.670 --> 00:05:08.810
WALTER ISAACSON: That was
the original intention

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:11.420
of the internet or
ARPANET was time

00:05:11.420 --> 00:05:15.220
sharing research computers,
and then collaborating.

00:05:15.220 --> 00:05:16.840
I even did that with this book.

00:05:16.840 --> 00:05:18.790
When I was writing
that, I said, wait,

00:05:18.790 --> 00:05:21.540
this is how we collaborate,
and I put parts of this book

00:05:21.540 --> 00:05:24.350
online, like on a medium
with Google Docs, whatever,

00:05:24.350 --> 00:05:25.810
and said, everybody share.

00:05:25.810 --> 00:05:26.780
Help me collaborate.

00:05:26.780 --> 00:05:28.300
Help put stuff in.

00:05:28.300 --> 00:05:30.620
And people like Stewart
Brand, who I knew,

00:05:30.620 --> 00:05:33.240
started rewriting the demise
of the Whole Earth Catalog,

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:36.490
and exactly what drugs were
being served at the demise

00:05:36.490 --> 00:05:38.810
partly because I
got the drugs wrong.

00:05:38.810 --> 00:05:40.740
But people like Dan
Bricklin were explaining,

00:05:40.740 --> 00:05:42.950
no, VisiCalc was done this way.

00:05:42.950 --> 00:05:45.690
And so they're in the book
from having been crowd sourced.

00:05:45.690 --> 00:05:48.040
BOB KAHN: Walter, I'd like
to ask you a question.

00:05:48.040 --> 00:05:51.630
Vint and I were both on a
panel at the National Academy

00:05:51.630 --> 00:05:57.210
about a week ago, and one of
the questions that came up was,

00:05:57.210 --> 00:05:59.670
what is the internet?

00:05:59.670 --> 00:06:02.560
One of the panelists
took the position

00:06:02.560 --> 00:06:05.810
that the internet is
what people think it is.

00:06:05.810 --> 00:06:07.750
So if you think the
web is the internet,

00:06:07.750 --> 00:06:08.950
then that's the internet.

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:10.830
If you think the web is this.

00:06:10.830 --> 00:06:13.990
I just wondered,
do you care much

00:06:13.990 --> 00:06:18.360
in writing a book like that
of clarifying that example.

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:20.310
Because a lot of places
in the book, you say,

00:06:20.310 --> 00:06:23.130
the ARPANET morphed
into internet, and not

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:28.042
exactly clear what the internet
is from reading your book.

00:06:28.042 --> 00:06:29.750
Are you comfortable
with that definition?

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:30.280
WALTER ISAACSON: I
see the internet,

00:06:30.280 --> 00:06:32.696
and I'm going to turn it to
you, because you should answer

00:06:32.696 --> 00:06:35.660
it better, but I see it
as the TCP/IP protocols.

00:06:35.660 --> 00:06:39.540
Now, the question is
when Tim Berners-Lee

00:06:39.540 --> 00:06:47.760
puts a layer of that [INAUDIBLE]
that have hypertext protocols

00:06:47.760 --> 00:06:52.790
and markup languages, to me,
that's still the internet.

00:06:52.790 --> 00:06:57.050
Now, the question then
becomes, if I'm using Twitter,

00:06:57.050 --> 00:06:58.140
is that the internet?

00:06:58.140 --> 00:06:59.827
And the answer
technically is no.

00:06:59.827 --> 00:07:00.660
I mean, that's not--

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:02.360
VINT CERF: Well, actually,
we could argue that because--

00:07:02.360 --> 00:07:03.320
WALTER ISAACSON: Oh,
we could argue it,

00:07:03.320 --> 00:07:05.100
so let me turn it
back to you all.

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:06.266
VINT CERF: Wait, wait, wait.

00:07:10.250 --> 00:07:13.610
You're right in the
middle of chapter six,

00:07:13.610 --> 00:07:15.790
and I wanted to at
least point out to you--

00:07:15.790 --> 00:07:16.800
WALTER ISAACSON:
Start at chapter one?

00:07:16.800 --> 00:07:19.216
VINT CERF: Well, we don't have
to go through every chapter

00:07:19.216 --> 00:07:22.710
but this starts out
with Ada Lovelace, who

00:07:22.710 --> 00:07:24.840
was Lord Byron's daughter.

00:07:24.840 --> 00:07:27.610
And I wanted to start
out by just asking, what

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:30.920
was it that drew you
to that story first,

00:07:30.920 --> 00:07:33.670
because it's in the
1850s in England,

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:35.870
and it's the earliest
manifestations

00:07:35.870 --> 00:07:37.521
of mechanical computing?

00:07:37.521 --> 00:07:39.020
What made you decide
to start there?

00:07:39.020 --> 00:07:40.478
WALTER ISAACSON:
To be honest, what

00:07:40.478 --> 00:07:44.300
drew it to me first was my
daughter had not written

00:07:44.300 --> 00:07:48.220
her college entrance essay,
and my wife, who we've talked

00:07:48.220 --> 00:07:52.270
about, was going nuts the way
Yuppie wives do, and saying,

00:07:52.270 --> 00:07:53.220
get it done.

00:07:53.220 --> 00:07:55.100
And one day, Betsy
said, I did it.

00:07:55.100 --> 00:07:56.820
I said, what was it on?

00:07:56.820 --> 00:07:58.370
She said, Ada
Lovelace because she's

00:07:58.370 --> 00:07:59.870
a computer geek and stuff.

00:07:59.870 --> 00:08:01.070
And I paused.

00:08:01.070 --> 00:08:03.250
I kind of knew the
name Ada Lovelace,

00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.030
but I didn't know
exactly what she did.

00:08:05.030 --> 00:08:06.430
VINT CERF: You didn't mix
it up with Linda Lovelace?

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:07.721
WALTER ISAACSON: No, I did not.

00:08:10.530 --> 00:08:15.130
I'm surprised that people
all remember who she is.

00:08:15.130 --> 00:08:19.030
So I became much more
interested in Ada Lovelace.

00:08:19.030 --> 00:08:21.960
Now, Ada Lovelace is partly
a symbol in this book,

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:25.900
because as a person, she's
kind of controversial,

00:08:25.900 --> 00:08:29.630
but what she does as
Lord Byron's daughter is

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:33.049
her mother, Lady Byron, was
optically fond of Lord Byron

00:08:33.049 --> 00:08:37.000
by the time Ada was growing
up, for reasons that Byron

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.429
fans will understand, and
so had her tutored mainly

00:08:40.429 --> 00:08:43.679
in mathematics as if that were
an antidote for her becoming

00:08:43.679 --> 00:08:47.180
a romantic poet, which Lady
Byron did not want her to be.

00:08:47.180 --> 00:08:50.220
So she embraces what she
calls poetical science.

00:08:50.220 --> 00:08:52.830
It's the ability to link
the poetic and the beauty

00:08:52.830 --> 00:08:57.650
of humanities with the
technology of science.

00:08:57.650 --> 00:09:00.660
She loves, for example,
traveling the Midlands

00:09:00.660 --> 00:09:03.650
and looking at the
punch cards that

00:09:03.650 --> 00:09:06.420
are being used in the mechanical
looms of the Industrial

00:09:06.420 --> 00:09:07.510
Revolution in the 1830s.

00:09:07.510 --> 00:09:08.580
VINT CERF: The
Jacquard looms, yes.

00:09:08.580 --> 00:09:10.220
WALTER ISAACSON:
The Jacquard loom,

00:09:10.220 --> 00:09:12.360
and showing how
they weave patterns.

00:09:12.360 --> 00:09:15.420
Her father, Lord
Byron, was a Luddite,

00:09:15.420 --> 00:09:17.750
and I don't mean
that figuratively.

00:09:17.750 --> 00:09:19.770
His only speech in
the House of Lords

00:09:19.770 --> 00:09:22.607
was defending the
followers of Ned Ludd, who

00:09:22.607 --> 00:09:24.190
were smashing these
looms because they

00:09:24.190 --> 00:09:28.220
were putting people out of work.

00:09:28.220 --> 00:09:30.400
And he also is there
with Mary Shelley

00:09:30.400 --> 00:09:32.200
when they do
Frankenstein's monster.

00:09:32.200 --> 00:09:35.390
This notion that
technology can destroy us

00:09:35.390 --> 00:09:38.910
was ingrained in Lord Byron.

00:09:38.910 --> 00:09:41.040
Ada felt the opposite.

00:09:41.040 --> 00:09:42.610
She had this friend,
Charles Babbage,

00:09:42.610 --> 00:09:46.240
who had made a pretty
good calculator called

00:09:46.240 --> 00:09:48.000
the difference
engine, was trying

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:49.440
to conceive one
which he never got

00:09:49.440 --> 00:09:51.420
built called the
analytical engine, which

00:09:51.420 --> 00:09:56.240
uses punch cards to do the
processing of the numbers.

00:09:56.240 --> 00:09:59.490
Ada writes a set of notes
that are totally fascinating.

00:09:59.490 --> 00:10:01.060
You've got to read them.

00:10:01.060 --> 00:10:03.410
And among the
notes to this thing

00:10:03.410 --> 00:10:07.530
is how if you use punch
cards, the machine

00:10:07.530 --> 00:10:10.190
will be able to weave
patterns like Jacquard's loom,

00:10:10.190 --> 00:10:11.320
as she puts it.

00:10:11.320 --> 00:10:14.620
In other words, the machine will
not only do numbers, she says.

00:10:14.620 --> 00:10:17.620
You can make it do
words, or even music.

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:20.310
I can feel her father
rolling over in the grave.

00:10:20.310 --> 00:10:24.720
Patterns, anything that can be
notated in symbols, she said.

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:28.480
So to me, that is
the core notion

00:10:28.480 --> 00:10:32.090
of what a computer is, anything
that can be notated in symbols.

00:10:32.090 --> 00:10:33.790
She has many other
things, but I'll

00:10:33.790 --> 00:10:36.650
only mention one, which
is her final note is

00:10:36.650 --> 00:10:38.380
that they'll do
anything but think.

00:10:38.380 --> 00:10:39.880
Machines will never be creative.

00:10:39.880 --> 00:10:41.680
Machines will never think.

00:10:41.680 --> 00:10:43.863
And 100 years later,
assuming you're

00:10:43.863 --> 00:10:47.390
going to jump there, Alan
Turing, who really comes up

00:10:47.390 --> 00:10:50.000
with the concept of the
universal computing machine,

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:54.600
and then works at Bletchley
Park to break the German ENIGMA

00:10:54.600 --> 00:10:55.740
code with some people.

00:10:55.740 --> 00:10:58.810
They build the Bombe
and then Colossus.

00:10:58.810 --> 00:11:02.600
He writes a wonderful paper.

00:11:02.600 --> 00:11:05.370
The movie's about to come out
called "The Imitation Game."

00:11:05.370 --> 00:11:07.050
He called it the imitation game.

00:11:07.050 --> 00:11:09.460
We now call the
Turing test to address

00:11:09.460 --> 00:11:12.710
what he calls Lady
Lovelace's objection,

00:11:12.710 --> 00:11:15.480
because Turing was
fascinated by Lovelace.

00:11:15.480 --> 00:11:17.940
And he says, well, you say
machines will never think.

00:11:17.940 --> 00:11:19.750
How would we know that?

00:11:19.750 --> 00:11:22.220
If you had a machine in a
different room and a person,

00:11:22.220 --> 00:11:24.230
you couldn't tell
their answers apart,

00:11:24.230 --> 00:11:28.590
you'd have no empirical reason
to say machines don't think.

00:11:28.590 --> 00:11:31.910
And so he believed in
artificial intelligence,

00:11:31.910 --> 00:11:35.900
that eventually, we would have
machines that think without us.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:38.870
I basically use that as
one of the framing devices

00:11:38.870 --> 00:11:41.950
in the book, the
notion of those who

00:11:41.950 --> 00:11:46.340
believe that the intimate
partnership between humans

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:48.830
and machines will get
us forward and those

00:11:48.830 --> 00:11:51.400
who believe that the pursuit
of artificial intelligence

00:11:51.400 --> 00:11:52.360
will get us forward.

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:53.860
Sorry for the long answer.

