00:14:50.560 --> 00:14:51.030
VINT CERF: That's right.

00:14:51.030 --> 00:14:53.446
BOB KAHN: I wanted to ask you
one question about something

00:14:53.446 --> 00:14:57.320
that struck me when I
first really understood

00:14:57.320 --> 00:14:59.600
what Turing and company
were doing at Princeton.

00:14:59.600 --> 00:15:04.540
I gave the keynote at the
100th anniversary of his birth.

00:15:04.540 --> 00:15:05.650
VINT CERF: His birthday.

00:15:05.650 --> 00:15:08.750
BOB KAHN: Last year [INAUDIBLE].

00:15:08.750 --> 00:15:11.420
It was one of a
multiplicity of them.

00:15:11.420 --> 00:15:13.440
But one of the
things that struck

00:15:13.440 --> 00:15:16.210
me back then was
when Turing wrote

00:15:16.210 --> 00:15:21.360
that paper on computable
numbers, that was actually

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.570
not easily accepted by people
because they didn't think

00:15:24.570 --> 00:15:27.720
computing was something that a
machine could do at that time,

00:15:27.720 --> 00:15:29.240
really.

00:15:29.240 --> 00:15:31.950
If you looked at what Church
did with the lambda calculus,

00:15:31.950 --> 00:15:33.410
it was a conceptual thing.

00:15:33.410 --> 00:15:36.160
If you looked at what his
colleagues, like Kurt Godel,

00:15:36.160 --> 00:15:39.340
and there were a number of
really excellent logicians

00:15:39.340 --> 00:15:41.330
there at the time,
they were thinking

00:15:41.330 --> 00:15:43.462
of conceptual frameworks
for organizing things

00:15:43.462 --> 00:15:44.670
so that the logic made sense.

00:15:44.670 --> 00:15:46.190
WALTER ISAACSON: You have
to remember that, as you do,

00:15:46.190 --> 00:15:48.160
uncomputable numbers
was not written

00:15:48.160 --> 00:15:50.284
to invent a universal
computing machine.

00:15:50.284 --> 00:15:51.700
That was just a
thought experiment

00:15:51.700 --> 00:15:55.840
he uses to solve
one of Hilbert's

00:15:55.840 --> 00:16:00.450
mathematical questions about
whether all problems are

00:16:00.450 --> 00:16:01.220
decidable.

00:16:01.220 --> 00:16:03.960
BOB KAHN: But it seems to me
that the one thing that really

00:16:03.960 --> 00:16:06.860
came out of that was the
idea that you could actually

00:16:06.860 --> 00:16:10.260
create a machine that would
do these computations.

00:16:10.260 --> 00:16:13.030
They eventually showed
that recursive function

00:16:13.030 --> 00:16:16.130
theory and the lambda calculus
and the Turing machine all

00:16:16.130 --> 00:16:18.730
could do all the
computable functions,

00:16:18.730 --> 00:16:23.190
but that wasn't known at the
time, nor was it obvious.

00:16:23.190 --> 00:16:25.690
The realization that
pops out at that time

00:16:25.690 --> 00:16:27.910
that you can actually
build something

00:16:27.910 --> 00:16:31.047
around these numbers
that was so fascinating,

00:16:31.047 --> 00:16:32.630
but I didn't get
that out of the book,

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:35.770
and I wondered, was that
something you just didn't think

00:16:35.770 --> 00:16:38.970
the public would
understand, or was--

00:16:38.970 --> 00:16:41.370
WALTER ISAACSON: I thought
that was important, totally

00:16:41.370 --> 00:16:42.010
fascinating.

00:16:42.010 --> 00:16:44.760
I drilled down, read
the entire Turing thing.

00:16:44.760 --> 00:16:46.610
That is a sideline
because it's not

00:16:46.610 --> 00:16:50.250
about the actual what they were
doing at Bletchley Park, which

00:16:50.250 --> 00:16:51.210
I was trying to tell.

00:16:51.210 --> 00:16:52.543
BOB KAHN: This was at Princeton.

00:16:52.543 --> 00:16:54.610
WALTER ISAACSON: Right.

00:16:54.610 --> 00:16:57.500
What happens there, and I
would love your feedback on it,

00:16:57.500 --> 00:17:01.190
is they are trying to figure
out whether all problems are

00:17:01.190 --> 00:17:03.590
computable, whether it's
decidable to know which ones

00:17:03.590 --> 00:17:05.280
or not, and you
end up with Godel

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:10.490
saying there's an incompleteness
inherent, and with Turing

00:17:10.490 --> 00:17:13.040
and Church both saying,
and we can't even

00:17:13.040 --> 00:17:17.240
decide what is completable
and what's not completable.

00:17:17.240 --> 00:17:18.980
I'm oversimplifying.

00:17:18.980 --> 00:17:21.490
So there's still
a mystery that's

00:17:21.490 --> 00:17:26.460
wonderfully inherent in math,
that not all things-- I mean,

00:17:26.460 --> 00:17:29.840
there is an incompleteness
in the mathematical system.

00:17:29.840 --> 00:17:31.540
BOB KAHN: But there
was also the fact,

00:17:31.540 --> 00:17:35.160
I believe, that
what Turing had done

00:17:35.160 --> 00:17:40.000
was not appreciated that much
by the other people around him

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:42.800
because they were the
pure theoreticians,

00:17:42.800 --> 00:17:45.850
and Turing was more
of an engineer,

00:17:45.850 --> 00:17:49.030
if I can use that term, even
though he never built anything,

00:17:49.030 --> 00:17:52.320
much like the conflicts that
we've seen in computer science

00:17:52.320 --> 00:17:53.920
in recent days
between the people who

00:17:53.920 --> 00:17:57.366
are the pure theorists and
the people who are actually

00:17:57.366 --> 00:17:57.990
building stuff.

00:17:57.990 --> 00:17:58.610
WALTER ISAACSON: You're
absolutely right,

00:17:58.610 --> 00:18:00.068
and I do say in
the book that there

00:18:00.068 --> 00:18:02.480
are only four or five people
who even comment or review

00:18:02.480 --> 00:18:03.080
his paper.

00:18:03.080 --> 00:18:05.030
It's not very well thought of.

00:18:05.030 --> 00:18:07.470
And throughout history,
you see that where Penn,

00:18:07.470 --> 00:18:09.790
they're building
these computers,

00:18:09.790 --> 00:18:12.380
and yet it seems a little
beneath their dignity

00:18:12.380 --> 00:18:15.590
because it's not an academic,
theoretical pursuit,

00:18:15.590 --> 00:18:17.170
so then they get
rid of the computer.

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:18.790
And even at Princeton,
if I may say,

00:18:18.790 --> 00:18:22.670
the IAS finally, after
von Neumann leaves,

00:18:22.670 --> 00:18:27.019
they don't feel computing is a
grand endeavor in its own way.

00:18:27.019 --> 00:18:28.435
BOB KAHN: Well,
there was physics.

00:18:28.435 --> 00:18:29.620
WALTER ISAACSON: Yes, right.

00:18:29.620 --> 00:18:30.660
VINT CERF: Well,
everything is physics

00:18:30.660 --> 00:18:31.910
when you get right down to it.

00:18:31.910 --> 00:18:33.930
WALTER ISAACSON:
Everything is math.

00:18:33.930 --> 00:18:34.870
VINT CERF: Well, OK.

00:18:34.870 --> 00:18:36.680
So we start with math
and we go to physics,

00:18:36.680 --> 00:18:38.700
and the abstraction of
physics is chemistry,

00:18:38.700 --> 00:18:40.730
and the abstraction of
chemistry is biology,

00:18:40.730 --> 00:18:42.607
and the abstraction of
biology is psychology,

00:18:42.607 --> 00:18:43.940
and it keeps on going like that.

00:18:43.940 --> 00:18:47.850
BOB KAHN: But you remember
the symposium we had up at MIT

00:18:47.850 --> 00:18:49.850
when Richard Feynman came
and a bunch of others,

00:18:49.850 --> 00:18:53.280
and it was called "The
Simulation of Physics,"

00:18:53.280 --> 00:18:55.530
and they didn't like that
one bit because they said,

00:18:55.530 --> 00:18:57.089
physics is not a simulation.

00:18:57.089 --> 00:18:59.380
It's not some bigger, digital
thing that's creating it.

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:00.630
WALTER ISAACSON: You're
losing control of the bus.

00:19:00.630 --> 00:19:02.630
VINT CERF: I'll come back
to a couple of things.

00:19:02.630 --> 00:19:03.880
Well, it's impossible.

00:19:03.880 --> 00:19:05.410
Nobody could manage these guys.

00:19:05.410 --> 00:19:08.370
But I do want to draw you back
for just a couple seconds.

00:19:08.370 --> 00:19:13.650
First of all, the point
about Turing, for example,

00:19:13.650 --> 00:19:16.400
reinforces the notion
that theory is helpful

00:19:16.400 --> 00:19:20.970
if you can underwrite or
underscore or somehow support

00:19:20.970 --> 00:19:21.730
applications.

00:19:21.730 --> 00:19:24.560
If you don't have much theory
underneath the application,

00:19:24.560 --> 00:19:26.410
then you don't quite
know what to expect

00:19:26.410 --> 00:19:27.970
and what you're doing.

00:19:27.970 --> 00:19:31.820
So it's clear that the
Gedankenexperiment that Turing

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:34.040
did is not unlike the
Gedankenexperiments

00:19:34.040 --> 00:19:36.360
that Einstein did.

00:19:36.360 --> 00:19:38.210
A lot of his work was not math.

00:19:38.210 --> 00:19:39.930
It was Gedanken imagery.

00:19:39.930 --> 00:19:41.149
He thought in those terms.

00:19:41.149 --> 00:19:42.940
WALTER ISAACSON: Visual
thought experiment.

00:19:42.940 --> 00:19:44.560
VINT CERF: Now let's go to
something more concrete,

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:45.110
though.

00:19:45.110 --> 00:19:46.780
You have a really
interesting story

00:19:46.780 --> 00:19:53.240
here about what happens when the
transistor gets built in 1947.

00:19:53.240 --> 00:19:59.050
The three guys who do this go
off-- well, Shockley anyway,

00:19:59.050 --> 00:20:03.290
goes off to start a company
to build transistors.

00:20:03.290 --> 00:20:04.980
And I think it's
worth recounting

00:20:04.980 --> 00:20:08.260
what happens because
the focus that we got

00:20:08.260 --> 00:20:10.364
to early in this game
was collaboration

00:20:10.364 --> 00:20:12.780
and what happens when you get
groups of people all focused

00:20:12.780 --> 00:20:14.310
on trying to do something.

00:20:14.310 --> 00:20:16.940
So what happens in that case?

00:20:16.940 --> 00:20:21.570
Shockley goes to the West
Coast and starts his company,

00:20:21.570 --> 00:20:23.930
brings some really
smart people together,

00:20:23.930 --> 00:20:27.250
which should have produced
an important collaboration.

00:20:27.250 --> 00:20:28.277
What happened?

00:20:28.277 --> 00:20:30.610
WALTER ISAACSON: It goes to
the theme of the book, which

00:20:30.610 --> 00:20:34.370
is that vision without
collaboration and execution

00:20:34.370 --> 00:20:36.166
is just hallucination.

00:20:38.850 --> 00:20:42.940
What you have at Bell Labs
is this wonderful environment

00:20:42.940 --> 00:20:45.966
where Shannon is riding a
unicycle up and down doing

00:20:45.966 --> 00:20:47.590
information theory,
but you also have--

00:20:47.590 --> 00:20:48.860
VINT CERF: Did he do
that when you were there?

00:20:48.860 --> 00:20:49.900
WALTER ISAACSON: Yes.

00:20:49.900 --> 00:20:51.910
BOB KAHN: Shannon had left.

00:20:51.910 --> 00:20:54.657
I started my career
at Bell Labs.

00:20:54.657 --> 00:20:56.240
One of the things I
got from your book

00:20:56.240 --> 00:20:57.660
that I found very
interesting was

00:20:57.660 --> 00:20:59.680
he started at the
same place that I did,

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:01.492
which was 463 West
Street in New York.

00:21:01.492 --> 00:21:03.575
WALTER ISAACSON: Right on
Greenwich Village's side

00:21:03.575 --> 00:21:03.950
of the Hudson.

00:21:03.950 --> 00:21:05.720
BOB KAHN: It was right
on the Hudson River,

00:21:05.720 --> 00:21:07.553
and you could watch the
Queen Mary and Queen

00:21:07.553 --> 00:21:09.012
Elizabeth coming
in every Tuesday

00:21:09.012 --> 00:21:10.220
and going out every Thursday.

00:21:10.220 --> 00:21:12.303
WALTER ISAACSON: It's still
a wonderful warehouse,

00:21:12.303 --> 00:21:14.510
and then they moved
it to New Jersey.

00:21:14.510 --> 00:21:17.020
BOB KAHN: Murray Hill existed
at the time that I was there.

00:21:17.020 --> 00:21:18.895
I think it probably
didn't when he was there.

00:21:18.895 --> 00:21:20.700
WALTER ISAACSON: It
becomes a cauldron

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:24.810
in which you have information
theorists, quantum theorists,

00:21:24.810 --> 00:21:29.375
like Shockley to some extent,
and certainly Bardeen.

00:21:29.375 --> 00:21:30.585
VINT CERF: Bardeen for sure.

00:21:30.585 --> 00:21:31.960
WALTER ISAACSON:
Walter Brattain,

00:21:31.960 --> 00:21:34.740
who is a great experimentalist,
but also people with grease

00:21:34.740 --> 00:21:37.600
under their fingernails who've
climbed a pole to figure out,

00:21:37.600 --> 00:21:40.620
how are we going to amplify
a phone signal between New

00:21:40.620 --> 00:21:43.990
York and San Francisco,
and they collaborate.

00:21:43.990 --> 00:21:45.960
They work together.

00:21:45.960 --> 00:21:48.530
They have a little
bit of a problem

00:21:48.530 --> 00:21:51.130
once the collaboration was
over, does Shockley get

00:21:51.130 --> 00:21:53.160
to be in the pictures
with Bardeen and Brattain,

00:21:53.160 --> 00:21:55.980
and who gets credit and
who gets a Nobel Prize,

00:21:55.980 --> 00:22:00.130
but before you fight over Nobel
Prizes, you collaborate well.

00:22:00.130 --> 00:22:03.480
Shockley was really
bad at collaboration,

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:06.910
and he got worse, and the
Nobel Prize didn't help.

00:22:06.910 --> 00:22:08.930
I'm glad we've not
all won one yet

00:22:08.930 --> 00:22:12.530
because it made him
into a bit of a jerk.

00:22:12.530 --> 00:22:16.680
He goes off and he forms
Shockley Semiconductor,

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:20.280
and he gets more and more
uncollaborative with his team,

00:22:20.280 --> 00:22:22.630
and more and more
top down dictatorial,

00:22:22.630 --> 00:22:24.330
unlike, say, a
[INAUDIBLE] environment.

00:22:24.330 --> 00:22:26.590
VINT CERF: Hiding his research
results from other people.

00:22:26.590 --> 00:22:27.740
WALTER ISAACSON: Hiding his
research from his own people,

00:22:27.740 --> 00:22:29.620
making them take
lie detector tests,

00:22:29.620 --> 00:22:31.620
worrying who's going
to get the credit.

00:22:31.620 --> 00:22:35.270
So obviously, the
great thing about it

00:22:35.270 --> 00:22:39.370
is it disintegrates because
of this, and the people who

00:22:39.370 --> 00:22:47.390
fly off from this big bang
are so allergic to Shockley's

00:22:47.390 --> 00:22:50.530
way of doing things that they
move to the other extreme, two

00:22:50.530 --> 00:22:54.930
of the best examples being
Gordon Moore and Bob Noyce,

00:22:54.930 --> 00:22:57.610
who form Fairchild
Semiconductor,

00:22:57.610 --> 00:22:59.220
and then eventually form Intel.

00:22:59.220 --> 00:23:00.990
VINT CERF: Why was it called
Fairchild Semiconductor?

