WALTER ISAACSON:
Because they did not

00:23:02.531 --> 00:23:04.150
have venture
capitalists back then,

00:23:04.150 --> 00:23:08.280
so they wanted to start their
own semiconductor company,

00:23:08.280 --> 00:23:10.880
but they couldn't just
go to Sandhill Road

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:14.140
and tell Kleiner Perkins,
give me an investment.

00:23:14.140 --> 00:23:16.535
Arthur Rock was just
starting, and so he

00:23:16.535 --> 00:23:17.700
helped put it together.

00:23:17.700 --> 00:23:20.600
Arthur Rock was not yet
a venture capitalist.

00:23:20.600 --> 00:23:22.570
He was still a
banker from the east.

00:23:22.570 --> 00:23:27.380
So he calls his east coast
buddies-- IBM, Bell-- and says,

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:29.360
do you want a
division we can start

00:23:29.360 --> 00:23:31.950
that will make semiconductors?

00:23:31.950 --> 00:23:33.630
And they'll say, no,
we don't want that.

00:23:33.630 --> 00:23:35.239
We don't want an
autonomous division.

00:23:35.239 --> 00:23:36.780
We don't want to
give them the power.

00:23:36.780 --> 00:23:39.710
He's just about to
give up and then went

00:23:39.710 --> 00:23:42.950
to Sherman Fairchild, who's a
bit of a nutcase and a playboy

00:23:42.950 --> 00:23:46.490
and always out in
nightclubs and 21 Club.

00:23:46.490 --> 00:23:48.950
They make a deal and
Sherman Fairchild says,

00:23:48.950 --> 00:23:50.890
yeah, I'll stake you.

00:23:50.890 --> 00:23:54.230
I'll make you a Fairchild
Semiconductor division.

00:23:54.230 --> 00:23:56.600
They were also doing
cameras and aircraft.

00:23:56.600 --> 00:23:58.630
And of course, it becomes
the biggest division

00:23:58.630 --> 00:24:01.510
in the company, and
eventually, Fairchild

00:24:01.510 --> 00:24:04.930
exercises the right to buy
them out, after which Noyce

00:24:04.930 --> 00:24:08.610
and Moore start their
own company, Intel.

00:24:08.610 --> 00:24:09.890
VINT CERF: That's amazing.

00:24:09.890 --> 00:24:12.940
So this is sort of like one
of those black hole explosion

00:24:12.940 --> 00:24:13.700
things that--

00:24:13.700 --> 00:24:15.825
WALTER ISAACSON: Well, they
call them fairchildren,

00:24:15.825 --> 00:24:18.490
because Fairchild
then breaks up a bit,

00:24:18.490 --> 00:24:21.644
and if you look at Silicon
Valley, you can do a Google map

00:24:21.644 --> 00:24:23.060
and just say
Fairchild, and you'll

00:24:23.060 --> 00:24:24.787
see all the companies
that spun off.

00:24:24.787 --> 00:24:26.370
BOB KAHN: You know,
there are actually

00:24:26.370 --> 00:24:29.490
two parallel stories with
Intel and the work that

00:24:29.490 --> 00:24:31.350
went on before that
are interesting.

00:24:31.350 --> 00:24:33.170
You focused on one
of them in the book,

00:24:33.170 --> 00:24:35.310
and I knew two of
those people very well.

00:24:35.310 --> 00:24:38.030
I've met Gordon Moore, but
I knew Bob Noyce very well,

00:24:38.030 --> 00:24:39.990
interacted with him a
lot, especially when

00:24:39.990 --> 00:24:42.660
I was doing the DLSI
program at DARPA

00:24:42.660 --> 00:24:45.710
and he was fighting the
VISIC program in the DoD.

00:24:45.710 --> 00:24:48.630
And the other was Andy
Grove, who was in my class

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:50.580
in undergraduate
school, so I knew him.

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:51.330
WALTER ISAACSON:
That's in New York.

00:24:51.330 --> 00:24:52.450
BOB KAHN: At City College, yes.

00:24:52.450 --> 00:24:53.550
So I knew those two well.

00:24:53.550 --> 00:24:56.180
But the other story
that's quite interesting

00:24:56.180 --> 00:24:59.677
is who gets the credit
for the microcomputer.

00:24:59.677 --> 00:25:01.135
WALTER ISAACSON:
The microprocessor

00:25:01.135 --> 00:25:02.520
or microcomputer?

00:25:02.520 --> 00:25:05.390
BOB KAHN: The
microprocessor in this case.

00:25:05.390 --> 00:25:07.890
VINT CERF: This is after the
integrated circuit, about which

00:25:07.890 --> 00:25:08.840
there was another big argument.

00:25:08.840 --> 00:25:09.798
BOB KAHN: That's right.

00:25:09.798 --> 00:25:14.400
This was in the early '70s, when
Intel was trying to figure out

00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:17.200
internally how you connect
one piece to another piece,

00:25:17.200 --> 00:25:20.660
and instead of
doing a one of, they

00:25:20.660 --> 00:25:22.650
decided, let's build
a programmable thing.

00:25:22.650 --> 00:25:26.330
So you have a guy named
Frederico Faggin, who actually

00:25:26.330 --> 00:25:29.100
did the actual
implementation of it.

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:32.640
You had a guy named Ted Hoff,
who is credited by everybody,

00:25:32.640 --> 00:25:35.580
and Bob Noyce told me,
when he was pushing

00:25:35.580 --> 00:25:38.140
some of the nominations
for awards for him,

00:25:38.140 --> 00:25:40.960
that he was sort of the
architect of the whole thing.

00:25:40.960 --> 00:25:42.700
But you had it all
done in a lab that

00:25:42.700 --> 00:25:44.830
was run by a fellow
named Les Vadez,

00:25:44.830 --> 00:25:46.950
and Les always
claimed that he set

00:25:46.950 --> 00:25:51.590
the environment and the tone,
which enabled it all to happen.

00:25:51.590 --> 00:25:53.900
Between three of them,
they don't really

00:25:53.900 --> 00:25:55.942
necessarily all see the
development the same way.

00:25:55.942 --> 00:25:57.608
WALTER ISAACSON: You
know, it's a shame,

00:25:57.608 --> 00:25:58.620
and that happens a lot.

00:25:58.620 --> 00:26:00.800
And in this book, I'm
already getting emails,

00:26:00.800 --> 00:26:01.720
and you are, too.

00:26:01.720 --> 00:26:03.900
I won't name names
because we're online,

00:26:03.900 --> 00:26:06.250
but people say, he didn't
quite give me enough-- oh,

00:26:06.250 --> 00:26:09.460
actually now I've read it,
he give me enough credit.

00:26:09.460 --> 00:26:13.960
The one I love is
Kilby, as you know,

00:26:13.960 --> 00:26:17.460
Jack Kilby does it at Texas
Instruments, the microchip.

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:20.580
I'm moving back earlier,
the integrated circuit.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:23.660
And Noyce does it at
approximately the same time

00:26:23.660 --> 00:26:25.480
and separately.

00:26:25.480 --> 00:26:28.924
And Kilby wins the Nobel
Prize, and unlike Shockley, it

00:26:28.924 --> 00:26:29.840
doesn't go to is head.

00:26:29.840 --> 00:26:33.380
And he also says, if Bob
Noyce was still alive,

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:35.780
he'd be sharing
this prize with me.

00:26:35.780 --> 00:26:36.840
They both deserve it.

00:26:36.840 --> 00:26:38.760
They don't give Nobel
Prizes when you're--

00:26:38.760 --> 00:26:40.570
VINT CERF: Kilby didn't get
that award until he was 82,

00:26:40.570 --> 00:26:41.750
and he passed away a
couple years later.

00:26:41.750 --> 00:26:43.833
WALTER ISAACSON: But when
they finally bring Kilby

00:26:43.833 --> 00:26:47.095
and he's awarded it, the
Norwegian scientist introducing

00:26:47.095 --> 00:26:51.400
him says, everything we have
in the digital revolution

00:26:51.400 --> 00:26:53.110
comes from what you did.

00:26:53.110 --> 00:26:56.960
And Kilby says, that reminds
me of what the beaver said

00:26:56.960 --> 00:27:01.110
to the rabbit at the
foot of the Hoover Dam,

00:27:01.110 --> 00:27:03.640
which is, no, I didn't
build it, but it

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:05.360
is based on an idea of mine.

00:27:08.072 --> 00:27:11.010
One of the things
about collaboration

00:27:11.010 --> 00:27:13.870
is it gets hard to
allocate credit,

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:17.140
and I try very hard
in this book to say,

00:27:17.140 --> 00:27:21.960
OK, here's how I would parse
the credit for the computer.

00:27:21.960 --> 00:27:25.470
I mean, is it basically
Mauchly and Eckert at Penn?

00:27:25.470 --> 00:27:29.760
Is it Atanasoff at Iowa State?

00:27:29.760 --> 00:27:32.830
Microchip, transistor?

00:27:32.830 --> 00:27:35.250
We all want to parse out
credit, whether we're

00:27:35.250 --> 00:27:39.390
intellectual property lawyers
fighting over the patents,

00:27:39.390 --> 00:27:42.550
whether we're Nobel
Prize jurists,

00:27:42.550 --> 00:27:47.470
or whether we're biographers,
and I tried to minimize,

00:27:47.470 --> 00:27:49.760
and you and I were
talking beforehand.

00:27:49.760 --> 00:27:53.750
There's dispute
amongst the people

00:27:53.750 --> 00:27:56.110
who conceived of
packet switching, which

00:27:56.110 --> 00:27:58.440
are three or four
or five people.

00:27:58.440 --> 00:28:01.180
They all fight over it.

00:28:01.180 --> 00:28:04.290
They're all quoted by name
on the record, will tell you,

00:28:04.290 --> 00:28:06.530
oh, this guy's an idiot.

00:28:06.530 --> 00:28:10.170
I try to say, no, it
was the collaboration.

00:28:10.170 --> 00:28:12.550
Packet switching
was an amazing idea.

00:28:12.550 --> 00:28:18.140
It is the heart of,
obviously, what you two did,

00:28:18.140 --> 00:28:21.220
and I was slightly
annoyed by the people who

00:28:21.220 --> 00:28:23.220
wanted to disparage
their colleagues'

00:28:23.220 --> 00:28:26.950
contribution because there is
enough credit to go around.

00:28:26.950 --> 00:28:31.400
VINT CERF: Exactly, and this
emphasizes several things.

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:33.500
The first one is a
lot of stuff happens

00:28:33.500 --> 00:28:35.600
because it's now
possible to happen.

00:28:35.600 --> 00:28:38.670
The economics are possible or
the amount of memory available

00:28:38.670 --> 00:28:43.270
makes it possible or the speed
of something makes it possible,

00:28:43.270 --> 00:28:45.930
and so concurrent
invention is not

00:28:45.930 --> 00:28:47.384
unusual under those
circumstances.

00:28:47.384 --> 00:28:48.800
WALTER ISAACSON:
Especially, there

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:54.170
was a miracle year
of 1939, let me say,

00:28:54.170 --> 00:28:58.000
where conceptual breakthroughs
have happened, including

00:28:58.000 --> 00:29:01.210
Turing's papers published
on universal computing,

00:29:01.210 --> 00:29:03.570
but Shannon and other
people are starting

00:29:03.570 --> 00:29:07.160
to apply Boolean algebra to
how to do it in circuits.

00:29:07.160 --> 00:29:12.020
But you also have mechanical
inventions, including

00:29:12.020 --> 00:29:14.065
the vacuum tube and
telephone switchboards,

00:29:14.065 --> 00:29:16.590
that have come together,
but you also have the drums

00:29:16.590 --> 00:29:20.180
of war, both in Germany
with Herman Zuse,

00:29:20.180 --> 00:29:22.240
and at Bletchley
Park in England,

00:29:22.240 --> 00:29:25.510
and at Aberdeen Proving
Ground in the United States.

00:29:25.510 --> 00:29:30.150
It's dawning on people that
firepower is actually not

00:29:30.150 --> 00:29:33.010
going to be as important as
computing power in winning

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:35.130
the next war, and
so that's why I'm

00:29:35.130 --> 00:29:38.280
convinced that you have a
fertile ground from 1940

00:29:38.280 --> 00:29:41.070
to '45 for the creation
of the computer.

00:29:41.070 --> 00:29:44.020
And likewise,
another fertile stew

00:29:44.020 --> 00:29:47.295
happens, which
Google is part of it

00:29:47.295 --> 00:29:50.280
out in California,
Mountain View and all,

00:29:50.280 --> 00:29:54.840
that in the early '70s, there
was just this yeasty brew

00:29:54.840 --> 00:29:57.845
of counterculture types,
electronic geeks, people who

00:29:57.845 --> 00:29:59.470
had been in the
defense industry,

00:29:59.470 --> 00:30:03.270
people who had read the Whole
Earth Catalog once too often,

00:30:03.270 --> 00:30:06.000
all of whom are coming
together and want computing

00:30:06.000 --> 00:30:09.760
power to the people to take it
back from the big corporations,

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:12.061
and they're creating the
Altair and the Apple and all

00:30:12.061 --> 00:30:12.685
those machines.

00:30:14.977 --> 00:30:17.310
VINT CERF: I was waiting for
you to leap into something.

00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:19.930
BOB KAHN: I have so many
thoughts going through my mind,

00:30:19.930 --> 00:30:22.650
I'm not sure where
to jump into this.

00:30:22.650 --> 00:30:25.620
One of the questions
I had about the book

00:30:25.620 --> 00:30:31.610
was, what prompted you
to choose the things

00:30:31.610 --> 00:30:32.990
that you did to emphasize?

00:30:32.990 --> 00:30:35.620
It's a wonderful read.

00:30:35.620 --> 00:30:39.300
WALTER ISAACSON: That's the
toughest of all questions.

00:30:39.300 --> 00:30:41.550
BOB KAHN: About the
only complaint I have is

00:30:41.550 --> 00:30:43.440
that you couldn't
touch everything

00:30:43.440 --> 00:30:44.930
with uniform treatment.

00:30:44.930 --> 00:30:48.700
So for example, there are things
that don't show up here at all,

00:30:48.700 --> 00:30:50.690
like, for example,
the role that NSF

00:30:50.690 --> 00:30:53.630
played in bringing
the internet out.

00:30:53.630 --> 00:30:56.220
There are people who I think
played an important role that

00:30:56.220 --> 00:30:58.714
never get mentioned, like
Steve Wolf is a good example.

00:30:58.714 --> 00:30:59.630
VINT CERF: Absolutely.

00:30:59.630 --> 00:31:00.630
Gordon Bell.

00:31:00.630 --> 00:31:03.180
BOB KAHN: I just wondered,
this is a reflection

00:31:03.180 --> 00:31:05.572
on what you felt you
wanted to write about.

00:31:05.572 --> 00:31:07.530
WALTER ISAACSON: I had
about a 1,000 page book.

00:31:07.530 --> 00:31:09.610
BOB KAHN: How did you
get to this rendition?

00:31:09.610 --> 00:31:11.060
WALTER ISAACSON: When
I did all my notes,

00:31:11.060 --> 00:31:12.268
there were about 1,000 pages.

00:31:12.268 --> 00:31:14.700
Wolf is in them, and
the other things.

00:31:14.700 --> 00:31:17.790
There's a certain limit
in this day and age

00:31:17.790 --> 00:31:20.590
to books, which is
approximately 500 pages.

00:31:20.590 --> 00:31:21.910
I mean, that's--

00:31:21.910 --> 00:31:23.701
BOB KAHN: I've read
books bigger than that.

00:31:23.701 --> 00:31:27.800
WALTER ISAACSON: I know,
but I meant-- not many.

00:31:27.800 --> 00:31:30.614
BOB KAHN: I read "Godel,
Escher, and Bach" in one swoop.

00:31:30.614 --> 00:31:32.280
WALTER ISAACSON:
That's what, 600 pages?

00:31:32.280 --> 00:31:33.000
Not much more.

00:31:33.000 --> 00:31:35.100
BOB KAHN: I think it
was more than that.

00:31:35.100 --> 00:31:36.910
WALTER ISAACSON:
That's a good book.

00:31:36.910 --> 00:31:38.522
BOB KAHN: One sitting.

00:31:38.522 --> 00:31:40.230
WALTER ISAACSON: Yeah,
but you know what?

00:31:40.230 --> 00:31:43.510
Not everybody can read
"Godel, Escher, and Bach"

00:31:43.510 --> 00:31:44.690
in one sitting.

00:31:44.690 --> 00:31:47.202
You're not the best focus group
for the publishing industry.

00:31:49.720 --> 00:31:54.520
But I did decide, hey, I want
to keep it in the package,

00:31:54.520 --> 00:31:56.020
and I'm going to
get to why we don't

00:31:56.020 --> 00:31:57.780
need to do that in the future.

00:31:57.780 --> 00:32:00.640
So I ended up picking 12.

00:32:00.640 --> 00:32:02.530
I just made a list
finally at the end,

00:32:02.530 --> 00:32:05.520
12 major things I wanted to do.

00:32:05.520 --> 00:32:11.080
I wanted to do the computer,
and so I focused on those three,

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:13.950
and by that, I mean the
people who really began it,

00:32:13.950 --> 00:32:17.110
not Control Data Corporation
and others that pick it up.

00:32:17.110 --> 00:32:21.371
I wanted to do the transistor,
the microchip, video games,

00:32:21.371 --> 00:32:23.120
because I actually do
think that they were

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:26.060
important in the
interactive computing realm.

00:32:26.060 --> 00:32:29.800
I wanted to do software
and how original

00:32:29.800 --> 00:32:31.810
operating system
software, and the women

00:32:31.810 --> 00:32:33.460
as well as men who did it.

00:32:33.460 --> 00:32:36.339
And I go down the
web and others.

00:32:36.339 --> 00:32:37.880
I could have picked
many other things

00:32:37.880 --> 00:32:39.588
and I could have picked
many other people

00:32:39.588 --> 00:32:42.580
in each one of those
categories, but I said, OK,

00:32:42.580 --> 00:32:47.010
who made a conceptual leap that
I really feel passionate about?

00:32:47.010 --> 00:32:50.310
Now, I know that leaves
out more than it includes,

00:32:50.310 --> 00:32:52.080
but it makes for a narrative.

00:32:52.080 --> 00:32:53.640
The problem with
narrative history

00:32:53.640 --> 00:32:56.840
is narrative is defined by
you leave out a lot of things

00:32:56.840 --> 00:32:58.194
so that you have a thread.

00:32:58.194 --> 00:32:59.860
BOB KAHN: But that's
really interesting,

00:32:59.860 --> 00:33:03.380
because if you focus it
all on the conceptual leap,

00:33:03.380 --> 00:33:06.970
you minimize the contributions
of the people who actually

00:33:06.970 --> 00:33:09.550
then implemented those ideas.

00:33:09.550 --> 00:33:12.697
As an engineer, and I think
Vint would agree with this, too,

00:33:12.697 --> 00:33:15.030
a lot of the details are in
making things actually work.

00:33:15.030 --> 00:33:16.530
WALTER ISAACSON:
Right, and I really

00:33:16.530 --> 00:33:18.600
try to emphasize in
the book that you

00:33:18.600 --> 00:33:21.100
have to execute on
vision, and that's

00:33:21.100 --> 00:33:25.640
why I focus on the engineers and
the software engineers of ENIAC

00:33:25.640 --> 00:33:27.440
more than on this
conceptual leap

00:33:27.440 --> 00:33:29.830
that Atanasoff has at
Iowa State because he

00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:31.070
doesn't implement it.

00:33:31.070 --> 00:33:33.710
And I hope-- I mean,
you can be the judge--

00:33:33.710 --> 00:33:36.250
that with Fairchild
and Intel, we

00:33:36.250 --> 00:33:41.060
get into a lot of the
engineers who are making it.

00:33:41.060 --> 00:33:43.300
Let me leap forward
to what I hope

00:33:43.300 --> 00:33:47.280
is the solution to this,
which is I would love it,

00:33:47.280 --> 00:33:50.090
and Google is the best
place to invent it

00:33:50.090 --> 00:33:54.346
with Google Docs,
networks, everything else,

00:33:54.346 --> 00:33:54.970
and I've tried.

00:33:54.970 --> 00:33:55.969
I've worked with people.

00:33:55.969 --> 00:33:58.030
I'm still not there
yet, but I would

00:33:58.030 --> 00:34:04.300
be quite happy to take this
book and make it a curated wiki

00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:08.120
Google Doc, and I have done
that with some of the chapters.

00:34:08.120 --> 00:34:10.120
It's why Dan
Bricklin-- you say, why

00:34:10.120 --> 00:34:12.020
is Bricklin in there
for doing VisiCalc?

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:14.840
Well frankly, because he
gave me all of his documents

00:34:14.840 --> 00:34:19.139
when he read an early draft
and it was on Medium, which

00:34:19.139 --> 00:34:22.690
is like a Google Doc
place where people put in.

00:34:22.690 --> 00:34:25.250
I think the book
of the future will

00:34:25.250 --> 00:34:28.969
be a collaborative,
crowd-sourced,

00:34:28.969 --> 00:34:33.580
and yet author curated,
meaning you just can't run off

00:34:33.580 --> 00:34:36.330
anywhere, multimedia,
where, let us

00:34:36.330 --> 00:34:40.929
say you want to talk about--
let's pick one thing--

00:34:40.929 --> 00:34:46.030
how the planar process worked
and how the planar process led

00:34:46.030 --> 00:34:51.070
to the microprocessor being
easily invented at Intel.

00:34:51.070 --> 00:34:54.300
I would love the videos, I'd
