00:40:50.440 --> 00:40:53.190
But generally, collaboration
is really cool.

00:40:53.190 --> 00:40:56.860
And I'll start, there's two
real segments of the internet.

00:40:56.860 --> 00:41:00.270
BOB KAHN: So when you
point out Vint and myself,

00:41:00.270 --> 00:41:01.520
what makes you single us out?

00:41:01.520 --> 00:41:03.020
I mean, we could
give you our views,

00:41:03.020 --> 00:41:04.360
but I'm wondering
what your views are.

00:41:04.360 --> 00:41:05.943
WALTER ISAACSON: I
will turn it around

00:41:05.943 --> 00:41:07.630
and make you give the views.

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:11.020
I'll say that there's
two great phases

00:41:11.020 --> 00:41:12.710
in the creation of the internet.

00:41:12.710 --> 00:41:15.280
Phase one was the
creation of ARPANET.

00:41:15.280 --> 00:41:17.024
I think you were
at BBN probably--

00:41:17.024 --> 00:41:18.815
BOB KAHN: I actually
was a system designer.

00:41:18.815 --> 00:41:21.540
WALTER ISAACSON:
Yeah, at BBN, right?

00:41:21.540 --> 00:41:25.380
Bolt, Beranek, and Newman, which
was a private company but still

00:41:25.380 --> 00:41:27.294
very associated with
MIT to some extent.

00:41:27.294 --> 00:41:28.210
BOB KAHN: And Harvard.

00:41:28.210 --> 00:41:30.210
WALTER ISAACSON: And
Harvard, and to some extent

00:41:30.210 --> 00:41:33.650
with the government, because
you had from Larry Roberts,

00:41:33.650 --> 00:41:36.170
and I guess the
original Licklider,

00:41:36.170 --> 00:41:41.290
you had contracts to do
what was unfortunately

00:41:41.290 --> 00:41:46.530
named IMPs, Interface
Message Processors, which--

00:41:46.530 --> 00:41:48.210
BOB KAHN: Why is
that unfortunate?

00:41:48.210 --> 00:41:52.011
WALTER ISAACSON: Well, because
when BBN got the contract--

00:41:52.011 --> 00:41:53.760
BOB KAHN: I actually
have the little slide

00:41:53.760 --> 00:41:54.930
that Ted Kennedy sent.

00:41:54.930 --> 00:41:55.910
WALTER ISAACSON: Yeah.

00:41:55.910 --> 00:41:57.650
I'm going to do a Ted
Kennedy joke here,

00:41:57.650 --> 00:42:01.366
which I'll let Dr.
Kahn do the punchline.

00:42:01.366 --> 00:42:02.990
BOB KAHN: I gave it
to Licklider's wife

00:42:02.990 --> 00:42:03.920
at the ceremony.

00:42:03.920 --> 00:42:05.670
VINT CERF: Wait, let
him do his punchline.

00:42:05.670 --> 00:42:06.220
WALTER ISAACSON: They
don't know the joke

00:42:06.220 --> 00:42:07.100
before you do the punch--

00:42:07.100 --> 00:42:08.030
VINT CERF: It's his punchline.

00:42:08.030 --> 00:42:08.790
Go ahead.

00:42:08.790 --> 00:42:09.623
WALTER ISAACSON: No.

00:42:09.623 --> 00:42:11.455
It's the Interface
Message Processor,

00:42:11.455 --> 00:42:16.020
and it's awarded to BBN, which
is in Ted Kennedy's district,

00:42:16.020 --> 00:42:19.030
and he sends a telegram
congratulating you

00:42:19.030 --> 00:42:20.410
on getting the--

00:42:20.410 --> 00:42:22.312
BOB KAHN: Inter-faith
message processor.

00:42:22.312 --> 00:42:23.770
WALTER ISAACSON:
Which, by the way,

00:42:23.770 --> 00:42:29.800
is a wonderfully telling slip,
because it was inter-faith,

00:42:29.800 --> 00:42:30.381
in many ways.

00:42:30.381 --> 00:42:31.880
VINT CERF: Well
actually, he thought

00:42:31.880 --> 00:42:33.610
he was congratulating
them on what

00:42:33.610 --> 00:42:35.330
he thought was an
ecumenical effort.

00:42:35.330 --> 00:42:36.022
WALTER ISAACSON: It was.

00:42:36.022 --> 00:42:37.550
It was the ultimate
ecumenical effort.

00:42:37.550 --> 00:42:38.590
VINT CERF: An inter-faith
message processor,

00:42:38.590 --> 00:42:40.310
the Jews and the
Muslims and the--

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:42.720
WALTER ISAACSON: We basically
call them routers now,

00:42:42.720 --> 00:42:44.920
but these were the machines
that were going to--

00:42:44.920 --> 00:42:46.820
BOB KAHN: Actually, I would say
we call them packet switches

00:42:46.820 --> 00:42:47.319
now.

00:42:47.319 --> 00:42:49.780
WALTER ISAACSON: Yeah, but
these were the machines

00:42:49.780 --> 00:42:53.350
that would be sent to the
original nodes on ARPANET that

00:42:53.350 --> 00:42:58.400
would be an inter-faith or
interface between the host

00:42:58.400 --> 00:43:00.360
machine and the
rest of the network.

00:43:00.360 --> 00:43:02.687
BOB KAHN: So Vint, you mean
if it wasn't ecumenical,

00:43:02.687 --> 00:43:04.520
we wouldn't have gotten
that thank you note?

00:43:04.520 --> 00:43:05.525
VINT CERF: I don't know.

00:43:05.525 --> 00:43:11.170
It was supposed to be something
that was nondenominational.

00:43:11.170 --> 00:43:14.020
The whole idea was
it's non-proprietary,

00:43:14.020 --> 00:43:17.720
and it was, from
Kennedy's choice of words,

00:43:17.720 --> 00:43:19.990
nondenominational,
and that's very true.

00:43:19.990 --> 00:43:22.220
The IMPs were there,
packet switches,

00:43:22.220 --> 00:43:25.350
to form this uniform,
homogeneous network

00:43:25.350 --> 00:43:28.050
to deal with an extremely
heterogeneous collection

00:43:28.050 --> 00:43:30.420
of computers that
were on the edges.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:32.480
And that demonstration,
to take your point

00:43:32.480 --> 00:43:37.480
about these two phases
of the whole process.

00:43:37.480 --> 00:43:40.480
The first phase demonstrated
that heterogeneous computers

00:43:40.480 --> 00:43:42.610
and operating
systems could be made

00:43:42.610 --> 00:43:46.570
to communicate across
a homogeneous network,

00:43:46.570 --> 00:43:48.591
and that was the
beginning of understanding

00:43:48.591 --> 00:43:49.340
what was possible.

00:43:49.340 --> 00:43:52.000
WALTER ISAACSON: And it was the
ultimate collaborative process,

00:43:52.000 --> 00:43:53.810
which is what I'm
going to ask you about,

00:43:53.810 --> 00:43:57.880
because if somebody had to
say, if you could show me

00:43:57.880 --> 00:44:01.280
the true nature of a
collaborative process-- this is

00:44:01.280 --> 00:44:04.790
early on, before we're
getting to the internet TCP/IP

00:44:04.790 --> 00:44:10.440
process-- is, how are these
IMPs going to communicate

00:44:10.440 --> 00:44:12.660
with host computers
and each other?

00:44:12.660 --> 00:44:15.780
And everybody vaguely
expected that, either

00:44:15.780 --> 00:44:19.770
from the bosses of BBN or
the bosses in the Pentagon,

00:44:19.770 --> 00:44:23.240
the word would be sent
down, but instead, it's

00:44:23.240 --> 00:44:26.337
done collaboratively
mainly by graduate student,

00:44:26.337 --> 00:44:27.920
including you were
a graduate student.

00:44:27.920 --> 00:44:30.490
BOB KAHN: There are actually
two parts of that process.

00:44:30.490 --> 00:44:34.340
The one that had the computers
talking to the other computers

00:44:34.340 --> 00:44:36.200
was what led to the
host to host protocols.

00:44:36.200 --> 00:44:37.970
That's one Vint was
very involved in,

00:44:37.970 --> 00:44:40.196
along with a number
of other people.

00:44:40.196 --> 00:44:42.820
And the second part that had to
do with how the machines talked

00:44:42.820 --> 00:44:47.850
to these interface message
processors was in a BBN report

00:44:47.850 --> 00:44:49.330
that I authored
called "BBN Report

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:54.070
1822," so that interface was
all called the 1822 interface,

00:44:54.070 --> 00:44:56.760
and that was a combination of
how the hardware would work,

00:44:56.760 --> 00:44:59.360
because you had different
word size machines, how

00:44:59.360 --> 00:45:01.790
the software would
work, and that

00:45:01.790 --> 00:45:04.350
was a precursor to having the
machines talk to each other.

00:45:04.350 --> 00:45:04.660
WALTER ISAACSON: Right.

00:45:04.660 --> 00:45:06.400
And the one I focus
on, because you

00:45:06.400 --> 00:45:08.150
asked, why do you
focus on things,

00:45:08.150 --> 00:45:11.460
is the request for
comment process,

00:45:11.460 --> 00:45:16.830
because it was so collaborative
and collegial, even the phrase

00:45:16.830 --> 00:45:19.120
that Steve Crocker, who you
turned me onto and I went

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:20.500
and interviewed for the book.

00:45:20.500 --> 00:45:22.670
He's just a graduate
student with you,

00:45:22.670 --> 00:45:25.230
and instead of having
the graduate student say,

00:45:25.230 --> 00:45:28.550
here's the way we
should do it, he said,

00:45:28.550 --> 00:45:30.650
I had to think of
a name that would

00:45:30.650 --> 00:45:33.576
make people feel like they
were collaborators in this.

00:45:33.576 --> 00:45:35.700
And so when we sent them
out, I didn't want to say,

00:45:35.700 --> 00:45:39.200
here's our plan or our proposal.

00:45:39.200 --> 00:45:41.780
He was standing in the shower
at his girlfriend's house,

00:45:41.780 --> 00:45:44.940
he said, and it
came to him that he

00:45:44.940 --> 00:45:47.220
should call it a
request for comment

00:45:47.220 --> 00:45:52.210
because it was so open and
inviting, as opposed to, here's

00:45:52.210 --> 00:45:54.617
what you're supposed to do.

00:45:54.617 --> 00:45:56.950
Let me let Vint tell the story
from there, and then Bob,

