00:57:30.820 --> 00:57:34.140
So I agree to give it a shot,
but only if I can have nothing

00:57:34.140 --> 00:57:36.952
to do with the ARPANET
because I did that before.

00:57:36.952 --> 00:57:38.160
I wanted to do something new.

00:57:38.160 --> 00:57:40.700
VINT CERF: Well, you would
have been constrained,

00:57:40.700 --> 00:57:43.140
in some sense, because
you were at BBN

00:57:43.140 --> 00:57:44.720
and they were
still a contractor,

00:57:44.720 --> 00:57:46.856
and you can't manage
them as a program manager

00:57:46.856 --> 00:57:48.720
after having been at BBN--

00:57:48.720 --> 00:57:52.250
BOB KAHN: This was before we
had conflict of interest rules.

00:57:52.250 --> 00:57:55.742
I mean, I got my own ability
to manage conflict, so not

00:57:55.742 --> 00:57:56.450
a problem for me.

00:57:56.450 --> 00:57:57.230
VINT CERF: No
conflict, no interest.

00:57:57.230 --> 00:57:58.740
BOB KAHN: Not a problem for me.

00:57:58.740 --> 00:58:02.850
But I finally said, all
right, I'll give it a shot.

00:58:02.850 --> 00:58:07.050
I started the packet radio
program after I got to DARPA,

00:58:07.050 --> 00:58:10.070
and I started the packet
satellite program as a program.

00:58:10.070 --> 00:58:13.490
Now, let me just say,
Larry had started

00:58:13.490 --> 00:58:17.250
to fund BBN to turn a
satellite IMP into one that

00:58:17.250 --> 00:58:20.620
could use a satellite
as a modem relay.

00:58:20.620 --> 00:58:24.550
And one of the issues that
I had to deal with was, was

00:58:24.550 --> 00:58:25.550
that a good idea or not?

00:58:25.550 --> 00:58:26.700
I thought, no, it wasn't.

00:58:26.700 --> 00:58:29.330
Let's make the satellite
net a separate net

00:58:29.330 --> 00:58:31.490
by splitting it
out, and this was

00:58:31.490 --> 00:58:35.030
an interesting technical
discussion we had with BBN,

00:58:35.030 --> 00:58:39.300
because they were of the opinion
that this would be much more

00:58:39.300 --> 00:58:42.130
reliable if everything
was in an IMP,

00:58:42.130 --> 00:58:45.610
but that meant you could never
do the equivalent of putting

00:58:45.610 --> 00:58:46.740
a router in between it.

00:58:46.740 --> 00:58:48.865
You'd just lose complete
control because everything

00:58:48.865 --> 00:58:50.850
was memory to memory transfers.

00:58:50.850 --> 00:58:53.120
So we ended up
building a separate net

00:58:53.120 --> 00:58:54.100
on a satellite net.

00:58:54.100 --> 00:58:56.600
When Larry funded them, there
were no domestic satellites

00:58:56.600 --> 00:58:57.220
at all.

00:58:57.220 --> 00:59:00.290
There was no plan to use
a satellite anywhere.

00:59:00.290 --> 00:59:04.210
And so I ended up
negotiating with COMSAT,

00:59:04.210 --> 00:59:07.280
and then an Intel sat
to actually set up

00:59:07.280 --> 00:59:09.590
tariffs that would
enable this to happen,

00:59:09.590 --> 00:59:11.460
and then we set up the program.

00:59:11.460 --> 00:59:14.740
The one who ran that program
technically was a fellow

00:59:14.740 --> 00:59:19.450
named Irwin Jacobs, who later
became the founder of Qualcom.

00:59:19.450 --> 00:59:22.590
I was sort of chief architect of
the packet radio program, which

00:59:22.590 --> 00:59:24.950
became essentially the
forerunner of today's CVMA

00:59:24.950 --> 00:59:25.670
technology.

00:59:25.670 --> 00:59:27.711
WALTER ISAACSON: The point
is that you have these

00:59:27.711 --> 00:59:30.176
all of these networks and
they don't interconnect.

00:59:30.176 --> 00:59:31.800
BOB KAHN: These three
networks show up,

00:59:31.800 --> 00:59:35.017
and that was what motivated
me to work on the problem

00:59:35.017 --> 00:59:37.350
of inter-networking them, and
I had some architectural--

00:59:37.350 --> 00:59:39.250
WALTER ISAACSON: Let me pause
right there because when I

00:59:39.250 --> 00:59:41.141
heard the word
"inter-networking," I said,

00:59:41.141 --> 00:59:41.640
I get it.

00:59:41.640 --> 00:59:42.280
That's where
internet comes from.

00:59:42.280 --> 00:59:42.863
Is that right?

00:59:42.863 --> 00:59:44.570
BOB KAHN: That's
where it came from.

00:59:44.570 --> 00:59:47.270
And so I had that as a goal.

00:59:47.270 --> 00:59:48.960
I had some architectural
principles.

00:59:48.960 --> 00:59:52.500
We knew about putting-- we
didn't call them routers then,

00:59:52.500 --> 00:59:54.440
we called them gateways.

00:59:54.440 --> 00:59:57.789
But I came from a
communications background,

00:59:57.789 --> 01:00:00.080
and so I was very comfortable
with building things that

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:03.040
could move the bits around,
but I was less comfortable

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:06.190
what the computers would do
with them when they got that.

01:00:06.190 --> 01:00:08.490
And Vint and I had
collaborated a lot

01:00:08.490 --> 01:00:13.120
on the ARPANET side of things,
me on the communications part,

01:00:13.120 --> 01:00:15.010
him on the computing part.

01:00:15.010 --> 01:00:17.830
He knew more about how
you embed these protocols

01:00:17.830 --> 01:00:20.374
into the end computers.

01:00:20.374 --> 01:00:22.040
I approached them at
one point and said,

01:00:22.040 --> 01:00:23.670
look, here's what
I'm trying to do

01:00:23.670 --> 01:00:25.420
and here's a whole
architectural approach.

01:00:25.420 --> 01:00:27.330
Here's what I really don't know.

01:00:27.330 --> 01:00:29.210
I don't know about
what it will take

01:00:29.210 --> 01:00:31.690
in these different machines.

01:00:31.690 --> 01:00:34.750
We agreed to collaborate, and
based on that collaboration,

01:00:34.750 --> 01:00:37.251
I think both parts of
it came out better.

01:00:37.251 --> 01:00:39.250
We were able to improve
the communications part,

01:00:39.250 --> 01:00:43.310
we were able to
improve the end part.

01:00:43.310 --> 01:00:46.230
I've had many collaborations,
but the one with Vint

01:00:46.230 --> 01:00:48.162
was probably one of
the best, and we've

01:00:48.162 --> 01:00:50.120
stayed pretty good friends
over the whole time.

01:00:50.120 --> 01:00:51.120
VINT CERF: In spite of that.

01:00:51.120 --> 01:00:52.540
BOB KAHN: In spite
of everything, right.

01:00:52.540 --> 01:00:53.480
WALTER ISAACSON:
That really does

01:00:53.480 --> 01:00:54.917
show that this
was a partnership,

01:00:54.917 --> 01:00:55.875
this was collaboration.

01:00:55.875 --> 01:00:57.630
BOB KAHN: Bit that's
where it came from.

01:00:57.630 --> 01:01:02.560
It came from the need to connect
all these different nets.

01:01:02.560 --> 01:01:07.810
WALTER ISAACSON: So explain how
you turned that into TCP/IP.

01:01:07.810 --> 01:01:10.950
BOB KAHN: Well, we
did it together.

01:01:10.950 --> 01:01:13.640
VINT CERF: He and I
spent six months trying

01:01:13.640 --> 01:01:17.370
to sort all this out, and
eventually, this notion

01:01:17.370 --> 01:01:20.962
of gateway-- the system sort
of emerged out of requirements.

01:01:20.962 --> 01:01:22.420
You have a bunch
of networks and we

01:01:22.420 --> 01:01:24.114
weren't allowed to
change any of them,

01:01:24.114 --> 01:01:25.530
and the question
is, well, if they

01:01:25.530 --> 01:01:28.370
can't know that they're part
of a distributed system,

01:01:28.370 --> 01:01:29.676
how do we link them together?

01:01:29.676 --> 01:01:31.300
The conclusion was
you needed something

01:01:31.300 --> 01:01:34.070
in between that knew how
to talk to both networks

01:01:34.070 --> 01:01:36.380
and would glue them
together even though they

01:01:36.380 --> 01:01:38.000
didn't know they were connected.

01:01:38.000 --> 01:01:40.367
Then the other problem is
that the hosts at the edges

01:01:40.367 --> 01:01:42.450
needed to be able to say
something like, send this

01:01:42.450 --> 01:01:45.150
to another network, but there
was no language for that

01:01:45.150 --> 01:01:45.650
because--

01:01:45.650 --> 01:01:46.370
WALTER ISAACSON: It was
like putting a postcard

01:01:46.370 --> 01:01:47.424
in another envelope?

01:01:47.424 --> 01:01:48.840
VINT CERF: Well,
the first problem

01:01:48.840 --> 01:01:51.430
is language because the
network that you were connected

01:01:51.430 --> 01:01:57.990
to locally had no vocabulary
for even understanding,

01:01:57.990 --> 01:02:00.260
take this thing and send
it to some other net.

01:02:00.260 --> 01:02:02.030
Every net thought it was
the only net in the world.

01:02:02.030 --> 01:02:03.863
BOB KAHN: I have to
tell you what addressing

01:02:03.863 --> 01:02:05.950
was like in the ARPANET,
16-bit addresses.

01:02:05.950 --> 01:02:08.220
When you sent something,
you said, essentially,

01:02:08.220 --> 01:02:10.000
send it to this wire.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:12.810
Imagine that every wire are
on the network was numbered.

01:02:12.810 --> 01:02:15.490
So you say, send
this to wire 17,

01:02:15.490 --> 01:02:17.920
and what was supposed to
be attached to wire 17

01:02:17.920 --> 01:02:21.490
was a big computer, so that
worked fine on the ARPANET.

01:02:21.490 --> 01:02:24.670
But if wire 17 then went
to some other net, which

01:02:24.670 --> 01:02:27.500
had a whole bunch of computers,
which of those computers

01:02:27.500 --> 01:02:28.230
was it for?

01:02:28.230 --> 01:02:29.730
There was no way that
language could describe it.

01:02:29.730 --> 01:02:30.090
VINT CERF: You
couldn't say that,

01:02:30.090 --> 01:02:32.494
so we had to invent the
internet protocol addressing.

01:02:32.494 --> 01:02:34.410
BOB KAHN: That's where
IP addresses came from.

01:02:34.410 --> 01:02:37.940
VINT CERF: And then we realized
that, in addition to that,

01:02:37.940 --> 01:02:40.910
of course, we had to make sure
that all the data that we sent

01:02:40.910 --> 01:02:42.700
in these little
postcard size pieces

01:02:42.700 --> 01:02:45.637
would be received and
reassembled at the other end,

01:02:45.637 --> 01:02:47.220
and we knew that
some of the networks,

01:02:47.220 --> 01:02:50.334
like the packet radio net and
the ethernet, would be lossy.

01:02:50.334 --> 01:02:51.750
There would be
radio shadow, there

01:02:51.750 --> 01:02:53.620
would be jamming and
all kinds of things,

01:02:53.620 --> 01:02:56.000
so we had to, on an
end to end basis,

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:58.009
make sure that the
communication was reliable.

01:02:58.009 --> 01:03:00.550
WALTER ISAACSON: So how did you
do that with the transmission

01:03:00.550 --> 01:03:01.510
control protocol?

01:03:01.510 --> 01:03:02.770
VINT CERF: Transmission
control protocol.

01:03:02.770 --> 01:03:05.490
Actually, the first papers that
we wrote had only one protocol.

01:03:05.490 --> 01:03:08.220
It was called TCP,
and it did everything.

01:03:08.220 --> 01:03:12.507
BOB KAHN: It had IP
integrated inside.

01:03:12.507 --> 01:03:14.340
VINT CERF: It solved
the addressing problem.

01:03:14.340 --> 01:03:17.600
It solved the end to end
retransmission and filtering

01:03:17.600 --> 01:03:21.300
out of duplicates, flow
control, and reordering,

01:03:21.300 --> 01:03:23.480
and everything was all
part of the one protocol.

01:03:23.480 --> 01:03:25.670
But after a few iterations,
finding some bugs

01:03:25.670 --> 01:03:29.140
in the design, several people
beat us over the head and said,

01:03:29.140 --> 01:03:31.310
we really need a way of
delivering things really,

01:03:31.310 --> 01:03:33.520
really quickly even if
not everything gets there.

01:03:33.520 --> 01:03:35.840
So we split the
internet protocol out

01:03:35.840 --> 01:03:39.440
from the TCP part, the
end to end reliable part,

01:03:39.440 --> 01:03:42.250
and then created something
called User Datagram Protocol

01:03:42.250 --> 01:03:44.596
so we could handle
real time traffic.

01:03:44.596 --> 01:03:46.720
WALTER ISAACSON: Let me
ask you a question I didn't

01:03:46.720 --> 01:03:50.300
ask for the book, which is,
if you had to do it all over

01:03:50.300 --> 01:03:52.770
again knowing what you
know now, what would you

01:03:52.770 --> 01:03:55.292
have designed differently?

01:03:55.292 --> 01:03:57.500
BOB KAHN: I would have
started with the digital logic

01:03:57.500 --> 01:03:59.750
architecture that I've been
working on for the last 20

01:03:59.750 --> 01:04:03.810
years, but that's not fair
because it's like saying,

01:04:03.810 --> 01:04:07.040
how would radio
communications in this country

01:04:07.040 --> 01:04:09.120
have evolved if
the semiconductor

01:04:09.120 --> 01:04:11.494
chip was available in 1915?

01:04:11.494 --> 01:04:13.410
You can't run that
Gedankenexperiment anymore.

01:04:16.150 --> 01:04:18.180
VINT CERF: But there
are things that I

01:04:18.180 --> 01:04:20.500
wish that we could have
done that we didn't,

01:04:20.500 --> 01:04:24.700
like I wish that we had picked
128-bit address space instead

01:04:24.700 --> 01:04:25.954
of a 32-bit address space.

01:04:25.954 --> 01:04:27.620
We wouldn't have to
go through this pain

01:04:27.620 --> 01:04:29.320
of the IPv6 transition.

01:04:29.320 --> 01:04:32.755
BOB KAHN: What makes you
think 128 bits is enough?

01:04:32.755 --> 01:04:34.130
VINT CERF: Well,
it might not be,

01:04:34.130 --> 01:04:35.921
but it'll be enough
until after we're dead.

01:04:35.921 --> 01:04:38.260
Then it doesn't matter.

01:04:38.260 --> 01:04:40.260
WALTER ISAACSON: Let me
talk about more consumer

01:04:40.260 --> 01:04:45.730
friendly things, rather than
addressable space, which

01:04:45.730 --> 01:04:49.100
is things like, is there
too much anonymity built

01:04:49.100 --> 01:04:49.850
into the internet?

01:04:49.850 --> 01:04:52.380
Would we be better off if
people were a little bit more

01:04:52.380 --> 01:04:54.810
responsible for
what they put up?

01:04:54.810 --> 01:04:59.020
BOB KAHN: I think that
identity in the internet

01:04:59.020 --> 01:05:00.790
is really important.

01:05:00.790 --> 01:05:02.830
I would like to see
us come to the point

01:05:02.830 --> 01:05:06.650
where everybody has unique and
persistent identifiers that

01:05:06.650 --> 01:05:09.277
resolve to reasonable state
information about them,

01:05:09.277 --> 01:05:10.860
and they can have
multiple identities,

01:05:10.860 --> 01:05:12.526
depending on the role
they want to play.

01:05:12.526 --> 01:05:15.730
And one of those roles we must
absolutely support, I think,

01:05:15.730 --> 01:05:17.105
is the role of anonymous.

01:05:17.105 --> 01:05:19.480
WALTER ISAACSON: So you'd have
an anonymous, pseudonymous

01:05:19.480 --> 01:05:21.012
thing.

01:05:21.012 --> 01:05:23.220
BOB KAHN: You can decide
how you want to participate.

01:05:23.220 --> 01:05:25.830
If I want to participate
as a government employee,

01:05:25.830 --> 01:05:28.330
I'm probably going to give a
government employee identifier.

01:05:28.330 --> 01:05:33.030
If I'm going to participate as
a representative of my company,

01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:36.230
that's a different one.

01:05:36.230 --> 01:05:39.750
And then maybe the services
and the opportunities you get

01:05:39.750 --> 01:05:41.834
are determined by how
definitive your identity is.

01:05:41.834 --> 01:05:43.333
WALTER ISAACSON:
But in other words,

01:05:43.333 --> 01:05:46.200
you could create an internet
in which there's secure ID,

01:05:46.200 --> 01:05:48.720
and when I'm dealing
with my bank,

01:05:48.720 --> 01:05:51.334
I would have to use
that identity when

01:05:51.334 --> 01:05:52.250
I'm dealing with them.

01:05:52.250 --> 01:05:54.910
BOB KAHN: Well, if this
were back in 1972 and Vint

01:05:54.910 --> 01:05:57.820
and I were doing it, I would
say, yes, we could do that.

01:05:57.820 --> 01:06:00.320
Today, I don't think
anybody can do that anymore

01:06:00.320 --> 01:06:03.830
because there's so many places
and parties around the globe.

01:06:03.830 --> 01:06:04.890
We can work toward it.

01:06:04.890 --> 01:06:07.630
VINT CERF: I actually think
it's possible to do some things,

01:06:07.630 --> 01:06:11.760
to create strongly
authenticated identities,

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:14.450
and also to achieve
some anonymity,

01:06:14.450 --> 01:06:16.867
but we're running out
of time, it turns out.

01:06:16.867 --> 01:06:18.450
BOB KAHN: But Vint,
I agree with that.

01:06:18.450 --> 01:06:21.550
I was harping on his
question about you.

01:06:21.550 --> 01:06:22.470
You could do it.

01:06:22.470 --> 01:06:24.511
VINT CERF: We've got to
let these other folks ask

01:06:24.511 --> 01:06:25.184
questions, too.

01:06:25.184 --> 01:06:26.850
WALTER ISAACSON:
Having three moderators

01:06:26.850 --> 01:06:29.510
is always hard, right?

01:06:29.510 --> 01:06:31.110
VINT CERF: So I've
got one question.

01:06:31.110 --> 01:06:32.365
Patrice?

01:06:32.365 --> 01:06:34.380
And then anybody else,
get your hands up.

01:06:37.450 --> 01:06:39.830
BOB KAHN: This is also my wife.

01:06:39.830 --> 01:06:41.840
I saw her come in.

01:06:41.840 --> 01:06:44.950
AUDIENCE: I'm going
to throw a softball.

01:06:44.950 --> 01:06:47.710
I've been sitting here looking
at your title, "Innovators."

01:06:47.710 --> 01:06:50.930
I started life out years
ago as a copyright attorney.

01:06:50.930 --> 01:06:54.060
I'm very much interested
in the creative process,

01:06:54.060 --> 01:06:56.285
and I've heard a lot
tonight about collaboration

01:06:56.285 --> 01:07:00.700
as if the spark of innovation
doesn't quite matter anymore,

01:07:00.700 --> 01:07:03.430
that it's some kind of muddled
group, they get together,

01:07:03.430 --> 01:07:05.290
and they come up with the idea.

01:07:05.290 --> 01:07:10.180
Now, I've worked with Bob
and Vint over the years,

01:07:10.180 --> 01:07:12.350
and I was listening
tonight to their discussion

01:07:12.350 --> 01:07:15.735
of the early days, which
that's an interesting story,

01:07:15.735 --> 01:07:19.450
but they each brought
their own innovation to it

01:07:19.450 --> 01:07:23.269
so you could have a finer
level of granularity.

01:07:23.269 --> 01:07:25.060
So you can have a
collaboration, but if you

01:07:25.060 --> 01:07:29.840
have a bunch of dullards and
one really bright card, then

01:07:29.840 --> 01:07:32.434
the collaboration really
is a useless concept.

01:07:32.434 --> 01:07:34.100
You have to look at
the innovation, what

01:07:34.100 --> 01:07:36.280
is the creative force?

01:07:36.280 --> 01:07:38.140
I'm trying to nuance
a bit because I

01:07:38.140 --> 01:07:39.580
heard the drumbeat of
collaboration a bit much.

01:07:39.580 --> 01:07:41.860
WALTER ISAACSON: That's why
it's a long book in a way

01:07:41.860 --> 01:07:44.590
because a lot of
collaborative teams

01:07:44.590 --> 01:07:46.270
don't work particularly well.

01:07:46.270 --> 01:07:48.590
I loved both the RFC
process, and then

01:07:48.590 --> 01:07:52.790
what you all talk about, about
the TCP/IP process, which

01:07:52.790 --> 01:07:54.880
is two people each
bringing, you're

01:07:54.880 --> 01:07:56.930
slightly more of a
communications mindset,

01:07:56.930 --> 01:08:00.790
whatever, but it ends up
being a collaboration where

01:08:00.790 --> 01:08:03.060
innovation really happens.

01:08:03.060 --> 01:08:04.970
Now, by the way, that
happens with Steve Jobs

01:08:04.970 --> 01:08:05.880
and Steve Wozniak.

01:08:05.880 --> 01:08:07.880
They are bringing different
things to the party.

01:08:07.880 --> 01:08:11.340
It certainly happened with
Andy Grove and Bob Noyce.

01:08:11.340 --> 01:08:15.590
One's a congregationalist who
loves singing madrigal songs

01:08:15.590 --> 01:08:17.600
in a congregational
church, and the other

01:08:17.600 --> 01:08:23.310
had to swim to escape the
Nazis and the Communists.

01:08:23.310 --> 01:08:25.859
I even tried to do that
with Benjamin Franklin,

01:08:25.859 --> 01:08:28.450
because he was not the
smartest of the founders--

01:08:28.450 --> 01:08:31.420
I mean, Jefferson,
Madison, and all--

01:08:31.420 --> 01:08:34.840
but he was the one who was the
glue who could bring together

01:08:34.840 --> 01:08:38.010
a Washington who's
indispensable,

01:08:38.010 --> 01:08:41.350
passionate people like
John and Sam Adams,

01:08:41.350 --> 01:08:43.369
smart people like
Madison and Jefferson.

01:08:45.910 --> 01:08:47.430
It's almost like
a baseball team.

01:08:47.430 --> 01:08:50.420
You need a pitcher, a
catcher, you need the manager,

01:08:50.420 --> 01:08:52.660
you also need
utility infielders.

01:08:52.660 --> 01:08:55.939
What makes for a collaboration
that has both a visionary

01:08:55.939 --> 01:08:57.180
but also executors?

01:08:57.180 --> 01:08:59.590
BOB KAHN: Walter, who was
the smartest of the founders?

01:08:59.590 --> 01:09:01.465
WALTER ISAACSON: The
smartest of the founders

01:09:01.465 --> 01:09:03.970
may have in-- I don't know.

01:09:03.970 --> 01:09:05.899
It's a good question,
and "smart" means

01:09:05.899 --> 01:09:07.109
many different things.

01:09:07.109 --> 01:09:08.676
I think Franklin
was really smart

01:09:08.676 --> 01:09:10.800
because he knew how to
bring smart people together,

01:09:10.800 --> 01:09:11.509
which is a skill.

01:09:11.509 --> 01:09:12.966
VINT CERF: Yeah,
but he was a twit.

01:09:12.966 --> 01:09:15.450
WALTER ISAACSON: I think Madison
was intellectually-- what?

01:09:15.450 --> 01:09:16.000
VINT CERF: He was a twit.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:16.999
WALTER ISAACSON: A twit?

01:09:16.999 --> 01:09:17.620
Franklin?

01:09:17.620 --> 01:09:18.703
VINT CERF: Yeah, Franklin.

01:09:18.703 --> 01:09:21.254
Well, I read your book.

01:09:21.254 --> 01:09:23.000
You spelled it out.

01:09:23.000 --> 01:09:26.670
WALTER ISAACSON: John Adams
was a twit, not Franklin.

01:09:26.670 --> 01:09:32.460
I think Madison was the
most creative mind there.

01:09:32.460 --> 01:09:34.438
Obviously, Jefferson
is very fertile mind,

01:09:34.438 --> 01:09:36.729
but we don't have to get into
a debate on the founders,

01:09:36.729 --> 01:09:39.950
as much as I have my
problems with Jefferson that

01:09:39.950 --> 01:09:42.410
go to the limits
of intelligence.

01:09:42.410 --> 01:09:44.560
VINT CERF: Let's let the
audience ask questions.

01:09:44.560 --> 01:09:45.011
WALTER ISAACSON: Susan?

01:09:45.011 --> 01:09:45.913
AUDIENCE: No, no.

01:09:45.913 --> 01:09:46.819
Who else has a question here?

01:09:46.819 --> 01:09:47.600
WALTER ISAACSON:
You're the moderator.

01:09:47.600 --> 01:09:49.260
I shouldn't be able
to pick out people.

01:09:51.877 --> 01:09:52.960
AUDIENCE: I'm Alex Howard.

01:09:52.960 --> 01:09:55.650
I've enjoyed reading your books,
following along, and using

01:09:55.650 --> 01:09:58.670
the internet for some time.

01:09:58.670 --> 01:10:02.200
I couldn't help noticing as I
opened this up that you have

01:10:02.200 --> 01:10:05.910
Ken Kesey in there, and
Stewart Brand, who you mention.

01:10:05.910 --> 01:10:09.100
If you look at the
people in this book,

01:10:09.100 --> 01:10:14.540
it's an American and British
story in a lot of ways.

01:10:14.540 --> 01:10:17.470
Since we're in DC and people
think about public policy

01:10:17.470 --> 01:10:21.880
here a lot, how you create
the conditions for innovation,

01:10:21.880 --> 01:10:25.265
if you look at that story,
how do you do that now,

01:10:25.265 --> 01:10:28.610
as people are thinking about
national competitiveness,

01:10:28.610 --> 01:10:31.020
about education,
about being inclusive,

01:10:31.020 --> 01:10:32.640
because STEM is a big issue?

01:10:32.640 --> 01:10:34.280
The impact of you
writing about this

01:10:34.280 --> 01:10:38.160
has caused quite a stir, too,
to recall the limit of ENIAC.

01:10:38.160 --> 01:10:43.060
It's important that the
original computers were women.

01:10:43.060 --> 01:10:45.200
When you think about the
conditions for innovation,

01:10:45.200 --> 01:10:46.940
what have you learned from
that, and what have you

01:10:46.940 --> 01:10:48.180
all seen, too, in terms of
the things being focused on?

01:10:48.180 --> 01:10:50.599
BOB KAHN: This is not a
question about genetics, right?

01:10:50.599 --> 01:10:51.640
AUDIENCE: Absolutely not.

01:10:51.640 --> 01:10:54.359
No, it's a condition about how
we create the next big thing.

01:10:54.359 --> 01:10:55.900
WALTER ISAACSON:
But it is a question

01:10:55.900 --> 01:10:59.400
about the primordial stew
from which the DNA emerges.

01:10:59.400 --> 01:11:03.050
VINT CERF: So at Google, I think
the most important ingredient

01:11:03.050 --> 01:11:05.840
for innovation is
permission to fail

01:11:05.840 --> 01:11:10.120
and the willingness to
let you try crazy ideas.

01:11:10.120 --> 01:11:12.860
The founders are
willfully determined

01:11:12.860 --> 01:11:15.346
that we will push the envelope.

01:11:15.346 --> 01:11:16.970
That's why we have
a Google X and we've

01:11:16.970 --> 01:11:19.220
got a moonshot
experiments and things

01:11:19.220 --> 01:11:21.290
that, like self driving cars.

01:11:21.290 --> 01:11:26.600
I think this attitude also
shows up in the Silicon Valley,

01:11:26.600 --> 01:11:29.440
where venture capital is
willing to accept risk.

01:11:29.440 --> 01:11:32.550
They know that maybe only 10%
of the things they invest in

01:11:32.550 --> 01:11:34.370
will actually work out.

01:11:37.320 --> 01:11:40.050
I don't think it's a
peculiarly American attitude,

01:11:40.050 --> 01:11:42.930
but it is an American
attitude, and I

01:11:42.930 --> 01:11:44.600
don't think we've lost that.

01:11:44.600 --> 01:11:47.084
I think we still have
it and we should use it.

01:11:47.084 --> 01:11:49.500
BOB KAHN: And that's also true
in DARPA to a large extent.

01:11:49.500 --> 01:11:50.583
VINT CERF: Oh, absolutely.

01:11:50.583 --> 01:11:53.820
BOB KAHN: They shoot high
and are willing to fail,

01:11:53.820 --> 01:11:57.310
even though they don't fail
too often because they often

01:11:57.310 --> 01:11:59.860
don't shoot as high as they
start out shooting for.

01:11:59.860 --> 01:12:01.360
WALTER ISAACSON:
I'd like to ask you

01:12:01.360 --> 01:12:02.720
a question on that, which is--

01:12:02.720 --> 01:12:03.700
VINT CERF: They're supposed
to be asking questions.

01:12:03.700 --> 01:12:04.090
WALTER ISAACSON: Oh, sorry.

01:12:04.090 --> 01:12:05.730
BOB KAHN: A lot of
success stories.

01:12:05.730 --> 01:12:08.021
WALTER ISAACSON: Well, I'll
just make a quick statement

01:12:08.021 --> 01:12:10.330
that I think we have blown
it a bit in government

01:12:10.330 --> 01:12:13.870
because it used to be you
were allowed to fail, and now

01:12:13.870 --> 01:12:16.000
any little gaffe you
make in this day and age,

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:18.660
you'll never get confirmed,
you'll get run out of town.

01:12:18.660 --> 01:12:22.250
In Silicon Valley, at least,
or in other innovative places,

01:12:22.250 --> 01:12:23.270
you're allowed to fail.

01:12:23.270 --> 01:12:25.370
I have Ken Kesey in
the book because it

01:12:25.370 --> 01:12:28.180
was a rebellious
attitude that happens

01:12:28.180 --> 01:12:31.740
in the late '60s and early '70s
in the Bay Area that involves

01:12:31.740 --> 01:12:33.490
"The Electric
Kool-Aid Acid Test"

01:12:33.490 --> 01:12:36.940
and Stewart Brand, and also
Doug Engelbart, as you know,

01:12:36.940 --> 01:12:38.500
with the mother of all demos.

01:12:38.500 --> 01:12:40.920
It's almost like one of the
electric Kool-Aid acid tests.

01:12:40.920 --> 01:12:44.770
It has Brand as the impresario.

01:12:44.770 --> 01:12:47.620
So part of that
cultural stew was

01:12:47.620 --> 01:12:52.040
the rebellious counterculture,
anti-war, anti-authoritarian,

01:12:52.040 --> 01:12:57.740
hippie, acid test mentality
that has been written about

01:12:57.740 --> 01:13:01.780
by Fred Turner very well,
by Steve Levy, John Markoff.

01:13:01.780 --> 01:13:05.600
Many people have written
about that hacker mentality,

01:13:05.600 --> 01:13:10.030
and it ties into the rebellious
as it allows you to fail.

01:13:10.030 --> 01:13:12.020
VINT CERF: Let's get
two or three questions

01:13:12.020 --> 01:13:14.330
asked, and then
we'll try to respond

01:13:14.330 --> 01:13:15.964
to them as a way
of getting more.

01:13:15.964 --> 01:13:16.880
Let's start over here.

01:13:16.880 --> 01:13:18.060
AUDIENCE: Hi, Jim.

01:13:18.060 --> 01:13:21.010
On the theme of collaboration,
with the internet

01:13:21.010 --> 01:13:24.900
hopefully going to be accessible
by the next four billion people

01:13:24.900 --> 01:13:28.390
on the earth's surface and
more than half the population,

01:13:28.390 --> 01:13:31.010
in terms of the global
innovator community

01:13:31.010 --> 01:13:34.330
and people's ability to
solve their own problems,

01:13:34.330 --> 01:13:37.000
what would you like the internet
to help do in the future

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:39.810
to solve global problems, to
connect people to collaborate

01:13:39.810 --> 01:13:42.452
on problems that seemingly
are insurmountable?

01:13:42.452 --> 01:13:43.910
VINT CERF: So global
collaboration,

01:13:43.910 --> 01:13:44.951
what can the internet do?

01:13:44.951 --> 01:13:46.890
Let's get a couple more.

01:13:52.710 --> 01:13:55.870
AUDIENCE: I really love "Steve
Jobs," the book, rather,

01:13:55.870 --> 01:13:59.150
and I'd like to ask
Mr. Isaacson, what

01:13:59.150 --> 01:14:01.030
are your impressions
of innovation

01:14:01.030 --> 01:14:03.180
at Apple after the
passing of Mr. Jobs,

01:14:03.180 --> 01:14:05.210
because it seems to
highlight that tension

01:14:05.210 --> 01:14:08.020
between a strong singular
visionary and then

01:14:08.020 --> 01:14:09.412
a collaborative team?

01:14:09.412 --> 01:14:11.120
I think there is a
storyline that there's

01:14:11.120 --> 01:14:14.187
been some drift since
you lost that visionary.

01:14:14.187 --> 01:14:14.770
VINT CERF: OK.

01:14:14.770 --> 01:14:16.140
So we've got
collaboration at Apple

01:14:16.140 --> 01:14:18.264
and we have global
collaboration over the internet.

01:14:18.264 --> 01:14:19.660
One more if there are?

01:14:19.660 --> 01:14:22.574
If not, we'll try
to tackle those two.

01:14:22.574 --> 01:14:23.490
There's one more here.

01:14:26.430 --> 01:14:28.060
AUDIENCE: So Mr.
Isaacson, how did you

01:14:28.060 --> 01:14:31.520
pick who the four people were
going to be on your book cover?

01:14:34.750 --> 01:14:36.020
VINT CERF: All right.

01:14:36.020 --> 01:14:38.410
AUDIENCE: I appreciate that
there's a woman up there.

01:14:38.410 --> 01:14:39.910
VINT CERF: I'm
pretty sure we're not

01:14:39.910 --> 01:14:42.560
going to be able to integrate
one answer to all that.

01:14:42.560 --> 01:14:44.350
Let's start with the
last one, book cover.

01:14:44.350 --> 01:14:45.936
How did you do that?

01:14:45.936 --> 01:14:47.310
WALTER ISAACSON:
Boy, it was very

01:14:47.310 --> 01:14:48.434
hard to do this book cover.

01:14:48.434 --> 01:14:50.190
I'm used to writing biographies.

01:14:50.190 --> 01:14:53.590
The Steve Jobs cover was
probably the most iconic cover,

01:14:53.590 --> 01:14:56.850
Steve Jobs and a picture,
so that's the easiest one.

01:14:56.850 --> 01:15:01.600
When you're doing something that
involves, say, 12 grand steps

01:15:01.600 --> 01:15:06.900
and 30, 40 innovators,
how do you pick them?

01:15:06.900 --> 01:15:09.720
In the end, it's Alan
Turing, if you're wondering,

01:15:09.720 --> 01:15:11.010
who's on the bottom right.

01:15:11.010 --> 01:15:14.207
You know the others,
Ada Lovelace.

01:15:14.207 --> 01:15:15.790
VINT CERF: They're
there the bookends,

01:15:15.790 --> 01:15:17.670
in some sense, and
then the rich guys.

01:15:21.324 --> 01:15:23.620
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
that's what I saw.

01:15:23.620 --> 01:15:27.000
WALTER ISAACSON: I think
that Steve Jobs and Bill

01:15:27.000 --> 01:15:31.110
Gates are very
emblematic characters

01:15:31.110 --> 01:15:33.510
of how you both have vision.

01:15:33.510 --> 01:15:37.450
Also, you execute, and business
execution is part of it,

01:15:37.450 --> 01:15:40.200
and collaboration.

01:15:40.200 --> 01:15:43.730
If I'd had 10 people,
I could have put 10.

01:15:43.730 --> 01:15:48.380
It was not a particularly
easy cover to do.

01:15:48.380 --> 01:15:51.970
If you go back and you
can find, Google things

01:15:51.970 --> 01:15:53.890
that are cached
from earlier times

01:15:53.890 --> 01:15:55.800
on Amazon, there's
probably eight

01:15:55.800 --> 01:15:58.509
covers that they went through
before they got to this one.

01:15:58.509 --> 01:16:00.050
VINT CERF: Actually,
maybe you should

01:16:00.050 --> 01:16:02.051
consider publishing a
book with multiple covers.

01:16:02.051 --> 01:16:02.966
WALTER ISAACSON: Yeah.

01:16:02.966 --> 01:16:04.470
At Time Magazine,
I used to do that.

01:16:04.470 --> 01:16:07.220
It was a real gimmicky, but
especially every now and then,

01:16:07.220 --> 01:16:10.260
you'd have four covers
for four different--

01:16:10.260 --> 01:16:12.590
VINT CERF: If collaboration
was the intent,

01:16:12.590 --> 01:16:14.690
I don't see collaborators
on the cover at all.

01:16:14.690 --> 01:16:16.680
Anyway, just a gripe.

01:16:16.680 --> 01:16:17.680
WALTER ISAACSON: Turing.

01:16:17.680 --> 01:16:18.763
Turing was a collaborator.

01:16:18.763 --> 01:16:19.810
VINT CERF: Well, mumble.

01:16:19.810 --> 01:16:22.882
OK, so let's go back to
this collaboration question.

01:16:22.882 --> 01:16:25.090
You've got this question,
how do you use the internet

01:16:25.090 --> 01:16:26.341
to help solve global problems?

01:16:26.341 --> 01:16:28.090
BOB KAHN: You want me
to take that one on?

01:16:28.090 --> 01:16:28.990
VINT CERF: Go ahead.

01:16:28.990 --> 01:16:31.460
BOB KAHN: I would
let's say you're

01:16:31.460 --> 01:16:33.740
thinking of the
internet writ large now.

01:16:33.740 --> 01:16:36.080
When I think of the
internet, I think about it

01:16:36.080 --> 01:16:38.654
in terms of the protocols
and the procedures

01:16:38.654 --> 01:16:39.820
that let you connect things.

01:16:39.820 --> 01:16:42.610
That gets back to the
definition of what it is,

01:16:42.610 --> 01:16:45.070
and then you can use it
for different things.

01:16:45.070 --> 01:16:47.545
So it really gets
into how people

01:16:47.545 --> 01:16:49.170
are going to get
together to solve some

01:16:49.170 --> 01:16:50.780
of these global
problems and what role

01:16:50.780 --> 01:16:52.240
the internet can play in it.

01:16:52.240 --> 01:16:53.580
You asked the question
the other way around,

01:16:53.580 --> 01:16:54.996
what can the
internet do for that,

01:16:54.996 --> 01:16:57.160
and I would say that's the
wrong way to get at it.

01:16:57.160 --> 01:16:58.941
The question is,
what global problem

01:16:58.941 --> 01:16:59.940
are you trying to solve?

01:16:59.940 --> 01:17:03.170
Is it clean water in
parts of the world that

01:17:03.170 --> 01:17:04.600
don't have access
to clean water?

01:17:04.600 --> 01:17:07.200
Is it how to get rid
of Ebola viruses?

01:17:07.200 --> 01:17:09.292
Is it how to do
checkout of people

01:17:09.292 --> 01:17:10.750
in airports when
they're coming in?

01:17:10.750 --> 01:17:13.260
Is it how to deal
with better targeting

01:17:13.260 --> 01:17:14.780
in the field for the military?

01:17:14.780 --> 01:17:17.350
You can figure out what
problem you're concerned about

01:17:17.350 --> 01:17:19.308
and then you can figure
out what a solution is,

01:17:19.308 --> 01:17:22.710
and then you can ask, is
these an internet role

01:17:22.710 --> 01:17:23.710
in all of that?

01:17:23.710 --> 01:17:27.110
And most likely, there will be
because everything is disparate

01:17:27.110 --> 01:17:30.270
and disconnected and you've
got to bring them all together.

01:17:30.270 --> 01:17:32.290
I wouldn't phrase
it exactly the way

01:17:32.290 --> 01:17:34.130
you did, starting
by asking about what

01:17:34.130 --> 01:17:35.450
the internet can do for you.

01:17:35.450 --> 01:17:37.854
It's the Kennedy
thing flipped around.

01:17:37.854 --> 01:17:40.020
VINT CERF: Ask not what the
internet can do for you.

01:17:40.020 --> 01:17:42.800
Ask what you can do
for the internet.

01:17:42.800 --> 01:17:45.850
I actually want to draw
out of this another notion,

01:17:45.850 --> 01:17:50.170
and that's the notion of
an enabling technology,

01:17:50.170 --> 01:17:52.040
because if you look
at these stories,

01:17:52.040 --> 01:17:56.430
all of them, what you see
is this scheme of things

01:17:56.430 --> 01:17:58.610
linking the stories together.

01:17:58.610 --> 01:18:01.050
Somebody creates
something, which

01:18:01.050 --> 01:18:05.330
enables someone else
to do another thing.

01:18:05.330 --> 01:18:08.270
This whole story is
all about enabling,

01:18:08.270 --> 01:18:11.920
which I think is part of
the origin of your question.

01:18:11.920 --> 01:18:14.260
What could the internet enable?

01:18:14.260 --> 01:18:16.430
The thing it does
better anything

01:18:16.430 --> 01:18:18.720
is it connects
stuff together that

01:18:18.720 --> 01:18:20.590
was never connected before.

01:18:20.590 --> 01:18:25.460
This casual idea that I can take
this can of Coke, for example,

01:18:25.460 --> 01:18:28.740
or this book, put a chip in it,
and connect it to the internet

01:18:28.740 --> 01:18:33.240
somehow is the
beginning of ideas

01:18:33.240 --> 01:18:35.470
that people never
thought of before

01:18:35.470 --> 01:18:37.570
because it wasn't possible.

01:18:37.570 --> 01:18:38.320
Now it's possible.

01:18:38.320 --> 01:18:39.480
BOB KAHN: Maybe you
don't connect it to it.

01:18:39.480 --> 01:18:42.220
Maybe it's automatically part
of it when you put the chip in.

01:18:42.220 --> 01:18:44.670
VINT CERF: Well, if we
ever get to the point

01:18:44.670 --> 01:18:47.890
where we can have self
assembling devices

01:18:47.890 --> 01:18:51.540
through biotechnology, then when
people say, what do you think,

01:18:51.540 --> 01:18:52.740
computers grow on trees?

01:18:52.740 --> 01:18:55.150
And you say, yeah,
let me show you.

01:18:55.150 --> 01:18:57.090
Let's go back to the
collaboration at Apple,

01:18:57.090 --> 01:19:00.030
though, because I think that
was a specific question for you

01:19:00.030 --> 01:19:00.830
to try to tackle.

01:19:00.830 --> 01:19:01.230
WALTER ISAACSON: Yeah.

01:19:01.230 --> 01:19:03.780
I mean, when I first started
writing about Steve Jobs,

01:19:03.780 --> 01:19:07.690
I thought he was an exception
to the rule about collaboration,

01:19:07.690 --> 01:19:11.050
that he was a singular visionary
and his visionary did things.

01:19:11.050 --> 01:19:13.180
And I asked him
at one point, what

01:19:13.180 --> 01:19:16.050
was your most visionary
thing that you created,

01:19:16.050 --> 01:19:20.590
and I thought he might say
the iPhone or iPad or the Mac.

01:19:20.590 --> 01:19:23.000
And he said, no, creating
a particular product

01:19:23.000 --> 01:19:25.140
or having a vision
for it is hard,

01:19:25.140 --> 01:19:28.380
but the really hard thing
is creating a company that

01:19:28.380 --> 01:19:31.365
lasts in which
people all know how

01:19:31.365 --> 01:19:34.990
to execute with vision
on various things.

01:19:34.990 --> 01:19:38.790
So the most important
thing I ever created

01:19:38.790 --> 01:19:41.800
was Apple because I
realized it wasn't about me.

01:19:41.800 --> 01:19:42.860
This is him talking.

01:19:42.860 --> 01:19:45.750
I realized it was about a team
of people where I could walk in

01:19:45.750 --> 01:19:48.030
and say, this sucks, or
this is great, or whatever,

01:19:48.030 --> 01:19:50.150
but eventually, out of
that sturm und drang

01:19:50.150 --> 01:19:53.160
would become a
particular product.

01:19:53.160 --> 01:19:56.650
And I think the most
important thing,

01:19:56.650 --> 01:19:59.290
and it's probably a
[INAUDIBLE] as here,

01:19:59.290 --> 01:20:01.030
whether it's Google
or Apple or whatever

01:20:01.030 --> 01:20:05.920
else, is to look at the
companies in which ingrained

01:20:05.920 --> 01:20:09.140
in the genetic code was a
willingness to take risk

01:20:09.140 --> 01:20:14.040
and to fail, and importance
about connecting beauty and art

01:20:14.040 --> 01:20:17.920
and humanity, making our
machines more personal

01:20:17.920 --> 01:20:20.450
so we felt intimate with them.

01:20:20.450 --> 01:20:23.240
There were a lot of companies
that came up with great ideas--

01:20:23.240 --> 01:20:28.210
Xerox at Xerox PARC, Bell
at Bell Labs, IBM, whatever.

01:20:28.210 --> 01:20:33.480
They didn't innovate as
a team and take risks.

01:20:33.480 --> 01:20:34.630
I see Google doing that.

01:20:34.630 --> 01:20:37.620
I'm not just saying it
because I'm here with you all.

01:20:37.620 --> 01:20:42.300
Google is one of the few really
big companies in which it's

01:20:42.300 --> 01:20:44.380
still like, let's
shoot for the moon,

01:20:44.380 --> 01:20:46.970
let's try some weird
things, and let's understand

01:20:46.970 --> 01:20:48.280
the importance of teamwork.

01:20:48.280 --> 01:20:49.620
I think Apple does that.

01:20:49.620 --> 01:20:52.110
Apple still has a team.

01:20:52.110 --> 01:20:56.180
What Steve did was not
just create a company.

01:20:56.180 --> 01:20:57.900
People read my
book and they say,

01:20:57.900 --> 01:21:00.700
Steve was pretty much of a
jerk at times, wasn't he?

01:21:00.700 --> 01:21:03.520
I say, yeah, but don't
forget how it turns out.

01:21:03.520 --> 01:21:06.546
He has the most loyal
people around him

01:21:06.546 --> 01:21:09.045
who will march through walls
with him, who will collaborate,

01:21:09.045 --> 01:21:10.880
who will stand up to him.

01:21:10.880 --> 01:21:13.910
That team at Apple
is a lot tighter

01:21:13.910 --> 01:21:16.342
than the teams at much
friendlier companies like HP.

01:21:16.342 --> 01:21:17.800
BOB KAHN: Walter,
one of the things

01:21:17.800 --> 01:21:19.310
that doesn't show
up in your book,

01:21:19.310 --> 01:21:23.520
and yet one is often drawn
to a comparison between Apple

01:21:23.520 --> 01:21:26.170
and Oracle, is Larry Ellison.

01:21:26.170 --> 01:21:28.222
Is he out of the picture
here because you just

01:21:28.222 --> 01:21:29.930
didn't have time to
get to him, or do you

01:21:29.930 --> 01:21:32.390
think he doesn't
play a role here?

01:21:32.390 --> 01:21:33.640
WALTER ISAACSON: I don't know.

01:21:33.640 --> 01:21:34.660
You tell me.

01:21:34.660 --> 01:21:36.667
BOB KAHN: No, you're the
one who wrote the book.

01:21:36.667 --> 01:21:37.750
Why did you leave him out?

01:21:37.750 --> 01:21:41.210
VINT CERF: Why don't
you [INAUDIBLE]?

01:21:41.210 --> 01:21:43.010
WALTER ISAACSON: I
don't know that Oracle

01:21:43.010 --> 01:21:46.720
was one of the 12 great
leaps of the digital age.

01:21:46.720 --> 01:21:49.560
I think Larry Ellison's
a brilliant person,

01:21:49.560 --> 01:21:55.917
but I don't find that the
creation of the Oracle systems

01:21:55.917 --> 01:21:57.750
was up there with the
transistor, microchip,

01:21:57.750 --> 01:21:58.666
the personal computer.

01:21:58.666 --> 01:22:00.620
If I may, I would
love to get back--

01:22:00.620 --> 01:22:02.700
BOB KAHN: I was just
curious as to your view.

01:22:02.700 --> 01:22:06.250
WALTER ISAACSON: So
what Steve is able to do

01:22:06.250 --> 01:22:11.920
is really show how you get
every player on a team,

01:22:11.920 --> 01:22:13.530
somebody like a
Tim Cook, who knows

01:22:13.530 --> 01:22:15.950
how to make things happen,
somebody like a Johnny

01:22:15.950 --> 01:22:18.280
Ives, who understands
the design,

01:22:18.280 --> 01:22:20.240
and he creates this tight team.

01:22:20.240 --> 01:22:23.870
I think at Google, too,
there is this ability,

01:22:23.870 --> 01:22:25.900
when you watch Larry
and Sergey, but then

01:22:25.900 --> 01:22:28.630
all the people around them
and all the people here.

01:22:28.630 --> 01:22:32.240
We can take risks, we can take
time off, we can collaborate,

01:22:32.240 --> 01:22:36.860
and I think that the most
important thing for innovation

01:22:36.860 --> 01:22:39.230
is not creating the
next new product

01:22:39.230 --> 01:22:43.770
but creating the Apples, the
Googles, the Amazons, whatever

01:22:43.770 --> 01:22:48.395
it may be, who are always
trying to do different things.

